<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens Control over Overseas Listing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The State Council, China's highest
governing body, released a circular today urging central and local
governments to tighten control over Chinese companies which issue
stocks overseas or are listed at overseas securities exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Chinese companies which are registered overseas, controlled by
Chinese assets and listed at overseas securities exchanges should
be supervised by local securities supervision organizations while
issuing stocks overseas.
</P>
<P>
Stock controllers of the Chinese assets must then report the
issuing to the China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC).
</P>
<P>
Chinese companies registered overseas can issue stocks abroad
or be listed at overseas securities exchanges provided they have
their assets inside China for more than three years, otherwise
they cannot. If necessary, their issuing must be examined by the
CSRC and approved by the Securities Commission under the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
As for overseas listing of the assets which are collected from
businesses inside China and transferred to overseas unlisted or
listed Chinese companies, Chinese stock controllers must notify
provincial governments or certain departments of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Those violating the regulations will meet tough penalties,
according to the circular. 
</P>
</TEXT>
