<HEADLINE> AIDS Education Urged in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Minister of Health Katele
Kalumba here today urged companies in the country to introduce
AIDS education at work places so as to reduce the loss of skilled
manpower through the scourge.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made at the opening of the Hiv/AIDS symposium for
truckers.
</P>
<P>
A speech read on his behalf at the function said the Truckers
Association should join in the fight against AIDS by changing its
members' sexual behaviors.
</P>
<P>
At the same function, Gary Davis, UNDP Resident Representative to
Zambia, said that the AIDS pandemic would be a major setback on the
future development of the country if people do not change their
lifestyle. He urged people in the productive sector such as the
industry to maintain their morals so that they can continue
contributing to national development.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government has invested a lot in people who are
currently in the industry and this would all go waste if they
continue dying of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The Truckers Association Chairman, Chaples Madongo, said that the
number of AIDS cases in the country has continued to rise even with
the availability of condoms. enditem

