<HEADLINE> Pak, India Trying to Arrive at A Mechanism: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmed said here today that Pakistan and India are trying
to arrive at some mechanism to resolve the outstanding issues
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is premature to say anything before time, we are trying our
best to arrive at some mechanism for the resolution of issues",
Ahmed told the media at the end of the first day foreign
secretary-level talks with the Indian side led by his counterpart
Salman Haider.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Foreign Secretary, when asked to comment on the
outcome of the first day talks, said, "We are moving in a
positive direction."
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the Indian side had the mandate to discuss the
Kashmir issue during the talks, Haider said that "the two sides
are in the process of identifying all the issues which will come
under discussion."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India began their new round of foreign
secretary-level talks here today. The talks are expected to last
for three days. The two countries held their previous round of
foreign secretary-level talks late March in New Delhi after more
than three years of suspension of the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
