<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: More Political Issues for Denver Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from the Group of
Seven industrialized nations and Russia are kicking off their
three-day summit by a grand dinner tonight hosted by U.S.
President Bill Clinton with more political issues on agenda than
it used to.
</P>
<P>
The summit is different from previous ones in two counts:
Russia's first full participation in the envent and no prominent
economic crisis around the world for the leaders to resolve.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who arrived here on Thursday
night, will participate all the events, both in political and
economic sectors, for the first time since Moscow was invited to
attend the summit in 1991.
</P>
<P>
But, the economic debates over interest rates and currency
values that have occupied leaders' attention for the past 22
summits will last one hour on Saturday afternoon without Yeltsin
present.
</P>
<P>
A draft final communique for the summit prepared for the past
four months by the eight countries is still under discussion by
the ministers and senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here say that the communique, which is due to be made
public on Sunday, is already clear on key goals.
</P>
<P>
Foremost is integrating Russia in the Western system, they say,
adding that the G-7 countries agreed to take several concrete
steps, such as letting Russia into the Paris Club and the World
Trade Organization (WTO) as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
However, Chief Deputy U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers
told local media that Clinton probably will not propose that
Russia become a full member of the G-7, changing the name to the
Group of Eight.
</P>
<P>
In the document, the leaders agree that open trade, fiscal
austerity and stable currencies is the best way to solve social
problems.
</P>
<P>
The economic talks will examine high unemployment in Europe and
how to resolve the problem of an aging population.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also generally agree on increasingly sophisticated
cooperative strategies for confronting an array of global problems
such as drug smuggling, nuclear safety and outbreaks of killer
infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
Despite consensus on many issues, leaders have sharp
differences to resolve during the summit.
</P>
<P>
Japan, which has a territorial dispute with Russia, is opposed
to a future full participation of Russia, arguing that Russia
needs to complete a lot of reforms in financial and other economic
areas.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. seeks to reward Moscow on acquiescing the expansion of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) by giving a strong
support to Russia's full participation.
</P>
<P>
For Russia, it seeks a phased integration into the system of
decision-making by the leading industrialized powers on most
important political, social-economic and monetary-financial
problems.
</P>
<P>
It insisted that Japan should not bring bilateral issues into
the multi-lateral process of the summit. Future full membership of
Russia in the group is in doubt.
</P>
<P>
As host, Clinton will push U.S. interests on several fronts. He
wants to rally support for the cleaning up in Chernobyl, Ukraine
after the 1986 nuclear reactor explosion. Clinton is expected to
ask for at least 300 million U.S. dollars from G-7 members.
</P>
<P>
But some European leaders are reluctant to pay more for the
project.
</P>
<P>
Other differences are likely to come from Europe as European
leaders walked into the summit amid doubts about Europe's
unification plans.
</P>
<P>
With their deficits higher than the three percent required for
joining European Monetary Union, France and Italy are concerned
about the fiscal criteria for the membership. Britain balks at
plans for military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Other political issues high on the agenda are Bosnia and Middle
East peace process. But analysts here say that there maybe no
concrete actions for pushing the process except some proposals or
sheer statements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
