<HEADLINE> Outlook for World Wheat Trade in 1997/98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 20 (Xinhua) -- World trade in wheat in 1997/98 is
forecast to expand by some 2 million tons, to 93.2 million tons,
International Grains Council (IGC) announced at its annual
conference which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
Global import needs are projected to rise further in 1997/98,
although recently improved supply prospects in India and China are
likely to limit the scope for any substantial increase in world
trade in 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
The growth in trade will result from rising consumption,
especially in Asia, and reduced crop prospects, particularly in
Northern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Trade in feed wheat, which expanded at a smaller than
anticipated rate in 1996/97, mainly because of higher than
forecast prices, is unlikely to rise further, unless significant
amounts of weather-damaged wheat become available.
</P>
<P>
Combined wheat output in the five major exporters (Argentina,
Australia, Canada, E.C, U.S.A.) is forecast to decline in 1997,
with some able to draw from accumulated stocks in order to
maintain aggregate export availabilities.
</P>
<P>
In view of the recent improvement in production prospects in
most of these countries, combined shipments in the year ending
June 1998 are projected to be the same as in the current year, at
87.5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Canada, in particular, will be able to use its larger 1996/97
carry-over to expand exports, forecast to increase by some 3
million tons, to 20 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The United States, expected to produce about the same amount as
in 1996, has seen only a modest recovery in stocks, but should be
in a position to increase its exports by some 1 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Exports by the European Community, estimated to harvest a crop
slightly below the previous year's, are likely to be broadly
unchanged from the 1996/97 figure of 16 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
