<HEADLINE> Big-Leaf Mahogany to Open to Controlled Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The 10th Conference of the Convention
on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) today listed
big-leaf mahogany species on Appendix Three which allows
lightly-controlled trade.
</P>
<P>
The compromise position was made at the last minute overturning an
earlier decision by the parties which rejected a proposal by Bolivia
and the United States to list the big-leaf mahogany on CITES'
Appendix Two, which allows strictly-controlled trade.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., the largest consumer of mahogany timber, said listing
the species would curb uncontrolled felling of the species threatened
to cause commericial extinction of the mahogany.
</P>
<P>
Bolivia, also a timber producer, said its proposal would enhance
cooperation between consuming and producing countries in conservation
programs.
</P>
<P>
However, Brazil, one of the range states, strongly contested
against the proposal saying this was coming just after it had
implemented its own measures to control indiscriminate harvesting of
the species.
</P>
<P>
During the plenary session today, Brazil and the U.S. finally
agreed to list the highly valued tree on Appendix Three, under which
mahogany trade would be controlled through the use of CITES export
certificates. enditem


=06201727

=06201733
NNNN
