<HEADLINE> Greece Welcomes U.S. Statement over Imia Islets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government today hailed
the U.S. statement over the Imia islets as "quite Significant."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon Thursday verified the
existence of an official navigational map issued by the U.S.
federal cartographical service showing the Imia islets as Greek
territory.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming Bacon's such statement, Greek Government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas also complained that since 1996, when
Turkey for the first time questioned the sovereignty of the Imia
islets, Washington had issued maps designating the islets also by
its Turkish name.
</P>
<P>
Imia, an uninhabited island with the area of 450 square
meters, is only 3.8 miles off the coast of Turkey in the Aegean
sea and 11 nautical miles from the Greek island of Kalimons.
</P>
<P>
Greece has insisted that the sovereignty of the island can not
be called into question while Turkey declared that the island
falls within the administrative limits of the Turkish province of
Mugla.
</P>
<P>
In early 1996, Greece and Turkey almost came to war over the
disputed island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
