<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Notifies UN on Treaties Applying to HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador Qin
Huasun today sent a note to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
two annexes covering 214 international treaties that will apply to
Hong Kong from July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Qin, Permanent Representative of China to UN, said in his note
that in accordance with the Sino-British Joint Declaration signed
on 19 December 1984, China will resume the exercise of sovereignty
over Hong Kong with effect from July 1, 1997. Hong Kong will
become a special administrative region, which will enjoy a high
degree of autonomy except in foreign and defense affairs, from
July 1.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the
Basic Law of Hong Kong, the international treaties, to which China
is a party, will apply to Hong Kong from July 1; the international
treaties, to which China is not a party but which are implemented
in Hong Kong, may continue to be implemented in the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region from July 1.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time that the Chinese representative sent
notifications to the UN Secretary General on international
treaties that will apply to Hong Kong from July 1. Chinese
ambassador Wang Xuexian sent notifications to the UN Chief on June
6 and June 10 on 24 and 16 international treaties respectively
that will apply to Hong Kong from July 1.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin said that the 127 treaties listed in Annex I to
the note, to which China is a party, will be applied to Hong Kong
with effect from July 1 as they are applied to Hong Kong before
July 1; or they fall within the category of foreign affairs or
defense or, owing to their nature and provisions, must apply to
the entire territory of a state; or they are not applied to Hong
Kong before July 1 but with respect to which it has been decided
to apply them to the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region with
the effect from that date.
</P>
<P>
The 127 international treaties in Annex I covers political,
diplomatic affairs and defense, narcotic drugs, international
crime, private international law, customs, marine pollution,
science and technology, civil aviation, merchant shipping,
investment, intellectual property, nature conservation, postal,
labor, human rights, international organization and trade.
</P>
<P>
The 87 treaties listed in Annex II to the note, to which China
is not yet a party and which apply to Hong Kong before July 1,
will continue to apply to the the Hong kong Special Administrative
Region from July 1.
</P>
<P>
The Annex II includes treaties on international crime, private
international law, customs, marine pollution, science and
technology, civil aviation, merchant shipping, trade, health,
property right, nature conservation, transport,
telecommunications, human rights, labor and international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The provisions of the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights and the International Covenant on Economic,
Social and Cultural Rights as applied to Hong Kong shall remain in
force beginning from July 1, 1997," Qin stressed in his note.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has already carried out separately the
formalities required for the application of the treaties listed in
the aforesaid Annexes, including all the related amendments,
protocols, reservations and declarations, to the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region with effect from July 1, he said.
</P>
<P>
"With respect to any other treaty not listed in the Annexes to
this note, to which the People's Republic of China is or will
become a party, in the event that it is decided to apply such
treaty to the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, the
Government of the People's Republic of China will carry out
separately the formalities for such application," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
"For the avoidance of doubt, no separate formalities will need
to be carried out by the Government of the People's Republic of
China with respect to treaties which fall within the category of
foreign affairs or defense or which, owing to their nature and
provisions, must apply to the entire territory of a state," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador also asked UN Secretary-General to place
the note and the Annexes to it formally on record and bring it to
the attention of the other members of the United Nations and the
specialized agencies of the United Nations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
