<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Militia Fight Koroma's Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between Sierra Leone's
military junta army and its traditional hunters known as Kamajors
has intensified since it broke out a few days ago, according to
reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors stood up to oppose the military junta of Major Johnny
Paul Koroma who has overthrown the civilian government and ousted
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in a coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, fighting started at about 9:30 Thursday
morning (9:30 am GMT) when the army attacked the Kamajors in the main
street of Kenema, eastern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
This was believed to be counter attack against the Kamajors'
assault on Wednesday on army bases in Kenema and Pujehun, southeastern
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general of the ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary
Council, Col. Abdulkarim Sise, reportedly alleged that Kabbah, Sierra
Leone's Ambassador to the United Nations James Jonah and Nigeria's
Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi had armed the Kamajors to fight the
junta.
</P>
<P>
He said considerable arms and ammunition, including food rations,
had been given to the Kamajors, while mercenaries had been hired from
Liberia to fight the army.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG has
vowed to restore the toppled civilian government. It is in the course
of military buildup for intervention when talks over the step-down of
Koroma fail.
</P>
<P>
Facing ECOMOG's imminent military intervention, the junta has
launched a series of diplomatic moves. A special envoy was in New York
on Wednesday to explain the situation in Sierra Leone to the United
Nations secretary-general and Security Council in a bid to seek their
support for a diplomatic solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The fate of the special envoy is yet to be known. But it is
reported that a 14-man delegation sent by Sierra Leone's military
junta to Gambia and Guinea received a cold shoulder. Gambian
President Yahya Jammeh even refused to meet the delegation on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Koroma's emissaries to Ghana and Cote d'Ivoire
also got the message from leaders of the countries that the coup
makers should step down and the ousted civilian government should be
restored.  
</P>
</TEXT>
