<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CITES Conference Hailed as a Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The 10-day conference of the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES)
ended in Harare this afternoon with delegates hailing it as a
success.
</P>
<P>
The conference considered 75 proposals on various species of fauna
and flora and made more than 60 resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The agenda of the conference was dominated by debates on
elephants, bears, whales, the southern white rhino and mahogany
species.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing ceremony, CITES Secretary-General Izgrev
Topkov said, ''we have laid in hare the foundation for an integrated
approach to development and conservation.''
</P>
<P>
He said the historic decision by the parties to downlist elephants
from the endangered species' list signalled a growing realisation by
the parties that sustainable use was necessary for conservation of
species.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Nambia and Botswana won their bid, amid firm opposition
from some western parties and non-governmental organisations, to
renew ivory trade on experimental basis in 1999 under strictly
monitored conditions.
</P>
<P>
Specified quotas from the three countries would be sold only to
Japan under the conditions set by the cites.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Environment Program Deputy Executive Director Rueben Olembo
said at the closing session it was important to realise that there
were no winners or losers at the cites.
</P>
<P>
''If we were to single out winners and losers, we must seek the
answer from the species, the ecosystems and habitants affected by our
actions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that effective mechanisms would be put in place by all
parties to implement resolutions of the conference.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the conference and Zimbabwe's Ambassador to the U.N.
Tichaona Jokonya described the conference as an overwhelming success.
</P>
<P>
He said the trends at the 10-day event had clearly pointed to an
increasing acceptance by parties of the legitimacy of sustainable
utilisation of natural resources.
</P>
<P>
The next CITES conference will be held in Indonesia in 1999.
enditem


