<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Standardization Authority Bans Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian standardization
authority today said it has banned the import of about 412 tonnes
of sheet iron and food items which it said lack the fixed
standard in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, head of the standard
control department in the authority Alemayehu Belete said 400
tonnes of sheet iron which sprung up from neighbouring Kenya was
banned from entering the country.
</P>
<P>
With regard to food item, he said 10 tonnes of less iodized
salt which came from Djibouti as well as 2.3 tonnes and 167 kgs
of packed food that came from Italy and Germany in that order
have similarly been banned from entrance for their packages were
damaged.
</P>
<P>
Alemayehu explained that the non-standard sheet iron usually
come from India, Turkey and Japan through sea ports.
</P>
<P>
He said 389 standards were set up by the authority for
agricultural, industrial, weight and measurement scales, adding
that there are about 116 mandatory standards whose absence may
result in the ban on the import of articles from abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
