<HEADLINE> All People Should be Involved for Earth Summit Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- All people should be
involved to achieve sustainable development and meet other goals
set at the Earth Summit five years ago, according to the
Worldwatch Institute.
</P>
<P>
The Worldwatch experts reported here today that so far
governments had fallen short of the goals agreed to by more than
100 world leaders in 1992 at the historic Earth Summit in Rio de
Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, human numbers had grown by 450 million, over
100,000 species of plants and animals had been lost, and annual
emissions for carbon dioxide from fossil fuels, the leading green
house gas, had climbed to all-time highes, the Worldwatch experts
noted.
</P>
<P>
Failure to achieve the Rio agenda could be seen in weak
implementation of the conventions on climate change and biological
diversity, and the lack of financing for various initiatives to
promote sustainable development, the Worldwatch experts said.
</P>
<P>
The budgets of the UN Development Program and Environment
Program had stagnated since Rio, and the Global Environmental
Facility, the major financial institution set up to support the
Rio agenda, had a 1996 budget of just 315 million dollars,
slightly below the 1992 budget of 322 million dollars, and less
than one-sixth the annual R &AMP; D budget of the Microsoft
Corporation, the Worldwatch experts added.
</P>
<P>
If the economy was to be put on a sustainable footing in the
twenty-first century, it was unlikely to be the result of a
top-down, centralized plan; the answer was more likely to lie in an
eclectic mix of international agreements, sensible government
policies, efficient use of private resources and bold initiatives
by grassroots organizations and local governments, the Worldwatch
experts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
