<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-20 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Motherland Party Leader Assigned to Form </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel today appointed Mesut Yilmaz, leader of the main
opposition Motherland Party (ANAP) to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the press center of the presidential
palace said that Demirel gave the mandate to Yilmaz to form the
55th government following his consultations with political party
leaders of the country.
</P>
<P>
The statement pointed out that Demirel asked Yilmaz, head of
the second largest party in Turkey after the Welfare Party (RP),
to form the government in a bid to eliminate the increasing
tension in the country.
</P>
<P>
Following his 45-minute-long meeting with Demirel, Yilmaz told
reporters that he will try to form the government in the
swiftest and quickest way.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz said that the nomination by Demirel is in compliance
with the democratic practice and the Turkish constitution.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution, when the cabinet formed by the first
party resigns, the mandate for forming a new government should be
given to the second largest one.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish constitution also requires a designated prime
minister to form a new government within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz is expected to hold talks with some social democratic
parties such as Republic People's Party (CHP), Democratic Left
Party (DSP), some DYP defectors and independent deputies in a bid
to drum up support for a broad-based new government.
</P>
<P>
If the new government failed to win a vote of confidance in the
parliament, then the mandate will naturally go to the DYP
Chairwoman Ciller, as her party is the third largest in the
550-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
In that case, the political dilemma will remain as it was when
RP leader Erbakan was forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Necmettin Erbakan, first Islamist prime minister
of Turkey, presented his resignation to Demirel and asked him to
appoint center-right True Path Party (DYP) leader Tansu Ciller to
form the new coalition government with the RP and with the support
of the Grand Unity Party (BBP).
</P>
<P>
Erbakan resigned because of the pressure from the military which
accused him of encouraging Islamic fundamentalist groups, posing
a serious threat to Turkey's secular system enshrined in its
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Repeatedly voicing their grave concern over the expansion of
fundamentalism in Turkey, the General Staff of the Turkish Armed
Forces has been exerting pressure on the RP-DYP coalition
government, resulting even in a military coup rumor in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
At a National Security Council meeting in February, generals
led by Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki Karadayi, demanded the
coalition government to take tougher measures against the
fast-increasing fundamentalist influence in this secular republic
but they were frustrated with the reluctance of Erbakan to curb
the Islamic radicals.
</P>
<P>
The ANAP and the DYP formed a minority coalition government in
March 1996 following the elections. But they proved to be rivals
rather than partners as the ANAP did not help stop parliament
motions against Ciller over alleged irregularities at the
Electricity Distributing Company (TEDAS), concerning corruption
allegations during the sale of state-owned shares of Turkey's
leading automobile plant TOFAS and for an inquiry into Ciller's
assets.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the ANAP-DYP coalition government collapsed on
June 6, 1996 after it lasted only for three months, clearing the
way for the coalition government of RP and DYP.
</P>
<P>
Observers here say the appointment of Yilmaz by the president
is just the outcome the military wanted though the president acted
according to the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The move outraged the RP and the DYP which claimed that the
designation is against the democratic rules and accused the
president of staging a coup.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister resigned and a new one selected, but the
politicians are still in a quagmire which is not easy for them to
get out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
