<HEADLINE> Leaders of G7, Russia to Open Summit in Denver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the seven
Western industrialized countries and Russia open their summit
meeting here today to discuss the major economic and political
issues.
</P>
<P>
The summit is hosted by U.S. President Bill Clinton and
attended by leaders from France, Britain, Germany, Italy, Canada,
Japan and the president of the European Council.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin also will attend the annual
summit from the beginning for the first time rather than being
relegated to a subsidiary role of joining the summit after the G7
economic agenda is completed.
</P>
<P>
Major economic issues on the agenda of the 23rd summit are
globalization, macro-economy in the U.S. and Europe, promoting
economic development in Africa, integrating Russia into the global
economy, reducing the threats to the global financial market and
the retiring baby boomer in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The summit opens at a time when the U.S. economy is on a modest
but stable expansion while some European nations including Germany
are in great difficulties with high unemployment and huge
government deficits.
</P>
<P>
In a scene-setting speech here Thursday, Clinton urged the G7
industrialized nations to follow the U.S. example and strengthen
the economies by abandoning "old ideas" and cutting the deficits.
The G7 leaders will have something to agree upon on the
macro-economical issues.
</P>
<P>
But there is also something to be at odds between the Western
industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto has said that Japan
wanted assurances from G7 leaders that Russia would be kept out of
key meetings on financial and macro-economic matters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the question of how to bring about growth and
stability in Africa will be featured during the summit and the
U.S. and France will express their different prescriptions on the
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
