<HEADLINE> Donors Conference for Bosnia Canceled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, June 20 (Xinhua) -- A late-June international
conference to assist Bosnia has been canceled due to the failure
of the country to reach an agreement with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
A statement released today by the World Bank and the European
Commission, which has organized the June 24-25 conference, said
that the participants had been informed "that the donors
conference has been canceled because, in the eyes of the donor
community, there has not yet been sufficient progress towards an
IMF agreement."
</P>
<P>
"As of this date, the donors conference has not been
rescheduled but should the recent rapid progress continue..., it
could take place in Brussels before mid-July," said Donato
Chiarini, head of the EC office in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
The IMF agreement is just one of the preconditions set by the
international community for convening the donors conference which
aims to raise reconstruction funds of 1.4 billion dollars for
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Under heavy pressure from the international community, the
Bosnian parties have recently met most of the requirements such as
an agreement with the World Bank and the adoption of a package of
basic economic laws.
</P>
<P>
An IMF agreement is essential to boost the donors' confidence
in the economic future of Bosnia and a prerequisite to successful
negotiations with the Paris and London clubs of official and
commercial creditors on debt reduction and rescheduling, the
statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
