<HEADLINE> Meteorological Satellite Sends Back First Cloud Picture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Meteorological
Satellite Ground Station received a clearly visible cloud picture
from a newly-launched meteorological satellite at 13:30 Beijing
time today.
</P>
<P>
This is the first cloud chart sent back to the Earth by Fengyun
2, a meteorological satellite launched on June 10 and successfully
stationed over the equator at 105 degrees east longitude a week
later.
</P>
<P>
The chart is believed to be another important achievement
Chinese scientists have scored so far with the Fengyun 2. The
successful processing of the picture proved that the multi-channel
scanning radiator, and instruction and data receiving station of
Fengyun 2 were operating normally.
</P>
<P>
The picture was received by the National Meteorological Bureau
and a team from the China Aerospace Corporation (CAC) during an
orbital test.
</P>
<P>
The scanning radiator of Fengyun 2 can view one third of
the Earth from a height of 35,800 kilometers, and can produce a
cloud picture every 30 minutes, allowing it to monitor weather
changes as they occur.
</P>
<P>
Fengyun 2 is the first meteorological satellite developed by
China that is in synchronous orbit with the earth. Covering about
100 million square kilometers of earth surface with China at the
center, Fengyun 2 can provide meteorological information such as
cloud pictures, temperatures, and wind movements over China and
its neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
