who leads the Arab Democratic Party, said the recent resignation
of a Likud minister risks withdrawal of the Russian immigrants'
Yisrael Be'aliya Party and the centrist Third Way from the ruling
coalition.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Finance Minister Dan Meridor resigned Wednesday after
an overnight seven-hour cabinet meeting on currency reforms,
saying that he had lost confidence in Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The crisis in the Israeli coalition has deepened, as two
ministers boycotted cabinet meeting Friday and the oppositions
are trying to secure a vote of no confidence in the Netanyahu
government.
</P>
<P>
Darawsha described the current crisis as "the negative
consequences of the policies" followed by Netanyahu on the
political and economic levels.
</P>
<P>
"Netanyahu's line of action vis-a-vis the Arab-Israeli
peace process raises stakes of more damage to the Israeli
ruling coalition," said the Israeli legislator.
</P>
<P>
But he ruled out the possibility that the Likud government may
not survive the no-confidence vote to be held at the Knesset next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The opposition must win 61 votes in the 120-seat parliament to
bring down the government. Yisrael Be'aliya holds seven of the
coalition's 66 seats in the parliament, and the Third Way has four.
</P>
<P>
According to an opinion poll broadcast on Israel's Channel 2,
up to 61 percent of Israelis have no confidence in
Netanyahu. While another poll, conducted by an Israeli daily, said
51 percent support early elections in their country.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 no-confidence motions have been defeated since the
Likud government took office last year. 
</P>
