President Clerides should attend direct talks and with good will
to make every effort so that progress on the protracted Cyprus
problem is achieved."
</P>
<P>
The House President noted that the U.S. and the European Union
(EU), both having close ties with Turkey, have "great
responsibility" in influencing Turkey in a correct way.
</P>
<P>
Both Clerides and the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash have
accepted the U.N. invitations to attend the face-to-face talks
designed to help break the stalemate in the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops had occupied the northern
third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash had two informal meetings in Nicosia
under the U.N. auspices, in October 1994, which ended in a
deadlock. They have not met ever since.  
</P>
