<HEADLINE> A Forward Movement in Pak-India Talks: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 21 (Xinhua) -- There has been a "forward
movement" in the current round of foreign secretary-level talks
here between Pakistan and India, a Pakistani Foreign Ministry
spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
"On the whole, there has been a forward movement in today's
talks," the spokesman told a press briefing here. The present
round of India-Pakistan talks began yesterday and is scheduled to
conclude on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"It was decided in today's session that each side will set down
its proposals in the form of working papers," the spokesman said.
"The two sides will work on those proposals tomorrow in an effort
to produce an agreed document."
</P>
<P>
The discussions were held in a "friendly atmosphere" and the
ideas of the two sides on various issues have now been
crystallized, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Indian Foreign Secretary Salman Haider, who
is leading the Indian delegation to the talks, called on
Pakistan's President Farooq Leghari and Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif.
</P>
<P>
At the meetings, both Leghari and Sharif emphasized the need to
work for the resolution of all outstanding issues between Pakistan
and India.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani leaders said "negative factors should be avoided
so as not to vitiate the atmosphere of these talks", according to
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said Haider conveyed the desire of the Indian government to
approach the dialogue in a positive spirit.
</P>
<P>
In answering a question, the spokesman said that "we will be
working to produce an agreed document tomorrow, and the basis for
the agreed document will be the proposals which will be set down
by each side today.
</P>
<P>
When asked to identify the "negative factors" which are likely
to vitiate the atmosphere of the on-going talks, Haider, who was
also present at the press briefing, said, "I don't want to go to
any details."
</P>
<P>
It is the second time that the two south Asian nations are
holding such kind of talks since March this year after a
suspension of over three years due to an increased tension in the
bilateral ties.  
</P>
