<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People across China Celebrate Hong Kong's Return Coming in 10 Days. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- It's just 10 days till Hong Kong
returns to the motherland, which means 10 days full of
celebrations and activities for Chinese people of all ages and
walks of life.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 college students from a dozen of Beijing-based
universities wrote heart-felt words on a 100-meter banner as a
gesture of goodwill for the return of Hong Kong to the motherland
on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The students, from Northern China Jiaotong University, People's
University of China, and the Central University for Nationalities,
will give performances on the evening of June 30 at Tiananmen
Square.
</P>
<P>
In another academic-related event associated with Hong Kong's
return, a seminar on the Treaty of Nanking was held today in
Nanjing, the capital city of east China's Jiangsu Province. Nearly
100 historians and experts discussed the impact of the Treaty of
Nanking -- the first unequal treaty signed in Chinese modern
history -- under which Hong Kong was ceded to Britain.
</P>
<P>
The participants agreed that Hong Kong's return was the result
of the successful practice of Deng Xiaoping's theory of "one
country, two systems." They also proposed that the 1,000-plus
out-of-date treaties signed in Chinese modern history should be
studied, and a new area of research should be developed to cover
the Opium War (1840-1842) and the nation's modern history.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, 100 workers who are skillful at calligraphy wrote
the Chinese character for "return" 100 times in different styles
on a 97-meter white scroll. The scroll will be stored by Shanghai
Museum as a momento of Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Fifty well-known Shanghai-based artists and calligraphers
together painted a picture on a scroll with 1,997 centimeters in
length and 66 centimeters in width today.
</P>
<P>
And Hong Kong's neighboring city of Shenzhen held an exhibition
on the flood relations between people of Shenzhen and Hong
Kong. Some 5,000-6,000-year-old cultural relics as well as
pictures illustrating the economic ties between the two places
were on display.
</P>
<P>
Rita Fan Hsu Lai Tai, President of the Provisional Legislative
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, viewed the
exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
