<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Young People Present Large Vessel to Motherland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A large new bronze vessel
presented by Hong Kong youth to the motherland was officially
unveiled today at Yuanmingyuan Park in northwest suburban Beijing.
</P>
<P>
There are only ten days left till the return of Hong Kong to
the motherland on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,000 young people from both Hong Kong and the Chinese
inland area attended the presentation ceremony this afternoon in
the largest area in the park, which had been the site of the
imperial garden of the Qing Dynasty and was destroyed by British
and French joint troops in 1860.
</P>
<P>
Amidst the celebratory sounds of drums and gongs, Chinese
officials and the representatives of the group of Hong Kong young
people uncovered the vessel.
</P>
<P>
It is modeled after the "Simuwu," an ancient square cooking
vessel with two looped handles and four legs, made during the
Shang Dynasty (1600 -- 1100 B.C.) to contain sacrificial offerings.
</P>
<P>
The 1,997-kg vessel is 2.22 meters high, two meters long and
1.5 meters wide, and bears the emblem of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region and some words in commemoration of the
return of Hong Kong to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong youth wanted the gift to express their best wishes
for the prosperity of the Chinese nation, said an official with a
Hong Kong youth organization.
</P>
<P>
Through today's event, the park will serve as a place of
patriotic inspiration for China's young people, said Liu Peng,
chairman of the All-China Youth Federation, at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Cheung Ming-man, a famous Hong Kong singer, performed a popular
song "I have a Chinese heart."
</P>
<P>
The activity was jointly organized by the Central Committee of
the Chinese Communist Youth League, the All-China Youth
Federation, and other organizations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
