<HEADLINE> China to Launch 10 Satellites for US Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The China Great Wall Industrial
Corporation (CGWIC) and the US-based Hughes Space and
Communications Company struck a long-term deal here today, under
which the Chinese aerospace company will launch 10 satellites for
Hughes from late 1998 through the end of 2006.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xinxia, CGWIC president, and Mr. Dorfmann, vice-president
of the Hughes' branch company in California, signed the agreement
involving the use of China's Long March launch vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The deal marks new progress made by the CGWIC in exploring the
international market of commercial launching services, after it
successfully put into orbit the Dongfanghong-3 communications
satellite and Fengyun-2 meteorological satellite in May and June,
using the Long March rockets.
</P>
<P>
The CGWIC is the sole body to receive state-approval for
conducting satellite launchings and designing and manufacturing
satellites. It has been working with Hughes since 1988.
</P>
<P>
It was also learned today that in the later half of this year,
China will provide commercial launching services to several other
satellites using its Long March rockets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
