<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Projects Underway to Improve Tie Between Shenzhen, HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, the only city with land
links to Hong Kong, is making greater efforts to ensure a smoother
flow of people and goods between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
A number of projects are underway for the purpose, including
restructuring of the city's traffic-ways.
</P>
<P>
Since Shenzhen was named a special economic zone (SEZ) in 1980,
it has invested two billion yuan to build up two land ports, seven
sea ports and an airport, and expand two other land ports.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 63.21 million people entered and departed from local
ports in Shenzhen, accounting for 45 percent of the country's
total. And 8.53 million vehicles came into and out of the ports,
according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has served as a bridge between Hong Kong and inland
areas; 80 percent of the container-trucks going to and departing
from Shenzhen's ports are working for the Zhujiang River Delta
area and inland provinces.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 60 percent of foreign trade goods in Shenzhen come
to or from inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming return of Hong Kong will make the economic ties
between the two places even closer, which in turn will accelerate
the transport volume between the two areas.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates by local experts, by the year 2000, the
land traffic volume between Hong Kong and Shenzhen is expected to
reach 68,000-70,000 vehicles per day, more than double the present
32,000 vehicles daily.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong returns to the motherland, Hong Kong and
Shenzhen are expected to work together on traffic-improvement
projects, including construction of a large highway bridge across
Shenzhen Bay to link up expressways on the two sides and the
building of a new waterway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
