<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Arab Action Against U.S. Move on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani today called for Islamic countries to take serious
measures against the latest decision by the U.S. lawmakers to
recognize Jerusalem as the capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 8th General Conference of the Organization of
Islamic Capitals and Cities (OICC) here today, Rafsanjani, in a
rare angry tone, criticized a number of Islamic leaders for
extending "silence welcome" to the U.S. move.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives approved the bill of
recognizing Jerusalem, a city viewed by Palestinians as the
capital of their future state, as the capital of Israel on June 10.
Many Arab countries have voiced anger over it.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani termed the move as an insult on Muslims.
</P>
<P>
He accused "certain Islamic countries" for being apathetic
toward the event, saying they keep "silence towards this
U.S. move."
</P>
<P>
He also criticized some others for according a warm and
friendly welcome to the U.S. defense secretary William Cohen right
after the adoption of the bill.
</P>
<P>
Cohen paid a five-day visit to Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain,
the United Arab Emirates and Oman in mid-June, during which he
said Iran is still the threat to the regional security.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani called on the mayors of Islamic countries to voice
their strong protest against the U.S. Congress' move so that the
Israelis would not have the impression that Muslim community has
become indifferent towards this issue.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem is revered among all Mulims as the site from which
Prophet of Islam, Muhammad, ascended to heaven.
</P>
<P>
More than 180 officials from 46 Islamic countries are
attending the three-day OICC gathering in Tehran to discuss city
planning, urban problems, environment protection and host of other
issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
