<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Residents Ready to Greet "Return Day" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- July 1 will become a special
public holiday for Hong Kong residents this year, a day for the
celebration of the region's return to China.
</P>
<P>
With this special day near at hand, a variety of celebrations
are being prepared by all sectors and strata of Hong Kong society.
The metropolis is immersed in an atmosphere of festivity.
</P>
<P>
In just 10 days from June 20 to 29, there will be more than 20
activities to be held in honor of Hong Kong's handover, ranging
from sports competitions, arts performance, special shows of
photos, pictures, paintings and books, scientific and
technological fairs, to recreation activities.
</P>
<P>
These programs, which are sponsored by all kinds of social
organizations and communities, are expected to draw an
unprecedented number of participants.
</P>
<P>
The celebration activities today include a stage play, a rugby
and a soccer contests, and a carnival.
</P>
<P>
In Kwai Tsing district on the southwest of Kowloon, a charity
ball has been held, for the purpose of commending the
contributions to community development made by major organizations
in the area, but also to raise fund for the Hope Project, a
project which aims to help providing children in relatively poor
areas in China's interior areas with proper education.
</P>
<P>
According to a local official in charge of the celebrations,
the district is aimed at enhancing its residents' sense of
belonging to the community, so as to promote among the residents
the feelings of patriotism and of loving Hong Kong and the
community.
</P>
<P>
On June 27, another special activity will be held. Then, the
200,000-strong contingent of taxies and minibuses running all over
Hong Kong will be bedecked with the flag of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), featuring a large Bauhinia.
</P>
