<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Rockets Guerrilla Base in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli warplanes carried out at
noon today an air raid at a suspected guerrilla base in south
Lebanon, in an apparent retaliation for an attack on Israeli
occupation forces in the so-called "security zone" in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said that the Israeli warplanes launched the
strike at 12:15 a.m. (0945 GMT) in Iglim Al-Toffah, a ridge some
65 kilometers southeast of Beirut which is often used by Muslim
guerrillas as a springboard to attack the Israeli self-carved
buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
The 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone" was declared by
Israel in 1985 in a pretext to protect northern Israel from
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Israel fighter-bombers fired two air-to-surface missiles
on the hill of Tellat Mlita in the area, the security sources
added, noting that no casualties were caused.
</P>
<P>
The air raid followed, and was followed by, artillery
bombardments at the heights and reconnaissance flights of Israeli
warplanes over the area, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Radio of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia
confirmed that the Israeli position of Bir Kalab deeply inside
the border strip had been attacked by guerrillas, but denied any
casualties.
</P>
<P>
In another development, six Irish soldiers of the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL), which is engaged in a peacekeeping
mission in south Lebanon, were wounded this morning as a result
of a mine explosion in the area of Beit Yahoun.
</P>
<P>
The six have been hospitalized in a field of the
multi-national forces in the south Lebanese border town of
Naqoura, and UNIFIl's spokesman Timor Goksel said that two soldiers
were in serious state while the four others were slightly injured.
</P>
<P>
Goksel said that the soldiers were wounded when patrolling a
road in Beit Yahoun inside the Israeli-occupied enclave "after
the UNIFIL was informed by the Israeli side that the road was
free of mines."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. force, comprising contingents from Fiji, Finland,
France, Ghana, Ireland, Italy, Nepal, Norway and Poland, was set
up in 1978 following the first Israeli incursion into the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the UNIFIL's installation, some 200 peacekeepers have
died and more wounded in various incidents on the last active
battlefront of the Arab-Israeli conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
