<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly Half Overseas Filipino Workers in Vulnerable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 45 percent of overseas
Filipino workers are in "vulnerable occupations," employed either
as domestic helpers or non-professional entertainers, the head of
a House committee said today.
</P>
<P>
Dante Liban, chairman of the House of Representatives Special
Committee on Overseas Filipino Workers, said women account for 95
percent of these vulnerable workers.
</P>
<P>
"Women also comprise the bulk of the estimated 1.8 million
undocumented, illegal overseas workers," Liban added.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Departments of Foreign Affairs and the Department
of Labor and Employment to focus their documentation and
protection efforts on these workers.
</P>
<P>
"Because they can easily be replaced, these unskilled workers
are far more susceptible to abuses by their employers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Liban said about 60 percent of the overseas Filipino workers in
vulnerable jobs are employed as housemaids while the rest are
working as entertainers.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has a total of six million overseas workers in
at least 100 countries and regions. They helped the country build
its economy by remitting 750 million U.S. dollars back last year.
</P>
<P>
However, cases of abuses against them have been increasing in
the past few years. It was reported that every day two overseas
Filipino workers died of abuses or in accidents last year.
</P>
<P>
At present, dozens of overseas Filipino workers are crying for
help in jails. How to help them while maintaining good relations
with these countries has become a headache for the Philippine
government.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the Philippines almost severed its diplomatic
relations with Singapore over the hanging of a Filipino maid in
the city state.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
