<HEADLINE> Italy Favors Dialogue on Human Rights: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government favors
dialogue and opposes confrontation on the issue of human rights,
Deputy Foreign Minister Patrizia Toia told a Chinese human rights
delegation today.
</P>
<P>
The delegation of the Human Rights Society of China is led by
Zhu Muzhi, who himself is president of the Human Rights Studies
Group. The mission is on the third leg of a four-nation European
tour of Norway, Sweden, Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Toia said that in the field of human rights, the Italian
government is a partner of dialogue and cooperation of China.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said he appreciated the Italian government's stance on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
It is quite normal that the East and the West have different
views on the issue of human rights just as on many other issues,
Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
The best way is to resolve the differences, he noted, is to
recognize them, find common ground through dialogue and increase
understanding and clear up misunderstanding through cooperation,
and finally reach consensus.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government stands for equal dialogue and
friendly cooperation on the human rights issue and opposes
deliberate confrontation and the imposition of ideas on others.
</P>
<P>
Like other issues, the issue of human rights could be
ultimately resolved so long as all countries engage in sincere
dialogue and cooperation, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Zhu and his delegation held talks with
vice-president of the Chamber of Deputies, Clemente Mastella, and
other Italian officials.
</P>
<P>
The two sides exchanged views on human rights, ethnic
minorities and relations between central and local authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
