<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Stresses Need for Water and Soil Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun stressed
during a recent inspection tour in northwest China that the area
must conserve water and soil resources and improve agricultural
production conditions.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also a member of Political Bureau of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) Central Committee, made the trip from June 16 to
21, mainly in Yulin Prefecture and the city of Yan'an in Shaanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
Yulin is located in a transit area between the Muus Desert and
the Loess Plateau, where there was formerly little vegetation and
local villages and farmland were threated by shifting sand.
</P>
<P>
Jiang was pleased to see that vegetation coverage in Yulin was
raised from the 1.8 percent in the early 1950s to 38.9 percent at
the end of last year. And there are 165 large tracts of woods and
four windbreak tree belts with a total length of 1,500 km.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the situation in early 1950s, the shifting rate
of sand dunes has diminished sharply, and the mud flowing into the
Yellow River has been reduced from 530 million tons to 190 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
In Yan'an, a city made famous during China's revolution, 78.4
percent of its area suffers from water and soil losses. By the end
of last year, 62 percent of the area was put under control. The
local ecological environment has been improved markedly and local
people's income raised to great extent.
</P>
<P>
The vice premier praised the local people for their efforts to
improve ecological environment and promote the local economy by
means of comprehensive development.
</P>
<P>
He urged local officials to aid the farmers by stabilizing the
central government's land contract policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Coup-makers Call for ECOWAS Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra Leone
has called for a meeting of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) to discuss intervention in the country's
political affairs.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today said the announcement, broadcast
through the Sierra Leonean National Radio, did not state when the
request was made or if there had been a response from the
regional organization.
</P>
<P>
The news was noted to coincide with the three-hour meeting on
Friday between a Ghanaian delegation and Major Johnny Paul
Koroma, leader of the country's ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary
Council (AFRC), in the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Koroma was formally sworn in as head of state on Tuesday
despite international condemnation of the coup on May 25 that
overthrew the elected civilian government led by ousted President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper "This Day" reported today that the talks
was part of a series of discussions initiated by west African
leaders to press the military junta to hand over power to
Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
The talks was held as fighting was reported to be going on in
Kenema, eastern Sierra Leone, between soldiers loyal to AFRC and
the Kamajors, traditional hunters loyal to Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a Kamajor spokesman as saying the Kamajors,
which had not retreated as the military demanded, were advancing
steadily toward Freetown after successfully pushing back the
military government troops.
</P>
<P>
The local militia, the Kamajors, reportedly to have put about
6,000 men on the battle front for the operation since Thursday
morning, vowed to march to Freetown and oust the military
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report said the AFRC secretary-general, Abdul
Susey, recommended on Friday the inclusion of Kabbah in round
table discussion in the search for a lasting solution to the
crisis in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Koroma has promised to establish a broad-based government made
up of all parties concerned in an election in due time, despite
growing international pressure to get him step down.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG is enhancing its
military buildup for an intervention in case negotiations for a
peaceful settlement of the Sierra Leonean crisis fail.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
