<HEADLINE> Pakistani PM Wants Meaningful Progress in Talks With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said today there should be meaningful progress in the
on-going foreign secretary-level talks between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
"The progress should be uniform on a broad spectrum of Indo-Pak
issues including the core issue of Kashmir," Sharif said during a
meeting with Indian Foreign Secretary Salman Haider, who is here
leading the Indian delegation to the current round of talks which
began yesterday.
</P>
<P>
There should be meaningful progress in the talks, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
The present round of talks are scheduled to conclude on Monday.
Pakistan and India resumed their foreign secretary-level talks in
March after a gap of more than three years.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release, Sharif also called for "reduction
of Indian forces and improvement of the human rights situation" in
the India-controlled Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the mutual spirit of the Summit of the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) in the Maldives
last month should be maintained to resolve all the outstanding
issues between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Salman Haider, while conveying greetings of Indian Prime
Minister Inder Kumar Gujral to Sharif, said Gujral had instructed
him to assure Sharif that India "wanted to open a new chapter in
the relations between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
India was aware of Pakistan's "concerns and pre-occupations
which they would try to address with sincerity and honesty," said
Haider.  
</P>
</TEXT>
