<HEADLINE> India's Gold Prices Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 21 (Xinhua)-- Gold prices in India's Mumbai
(Bombay) bullion market today dropped sharply in the absence of
any fresh buying interest.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that weak overseas advises also
dampened the sentiment.
</P>
<P>
As a result, standard gold dipped further to a record low of
4,605 rupees (129.72 US dollars) per 10 gram as against the
previous low level of 4,625 rupees (130.28 US dollars) per ten
gram quoted on June 13.
</P>
<P>
And 22-carat gold was also nominally quoted weak at 4,260
rupees (120 US dollars) as against yesterday's close of 4,280
rupees (120.56 US dollars). The tola gold bar lost 350 rupees
(9.86 US dollars) and finished at 53,850 rupees (1,516.90 US
dollars) from 54,200 rupees (1,526.76 US dollars) previously.
</P>
