<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Provisional Legislature Holds 12th Meeting in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) concluded its 12th and last plenary meeting here today
before Hong Kong's handover to China.
</P>
<P>
As of July 1, with the meeting venue shifted to Hong Kong, the
HK lawmakers will be relieved of shuttling between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
HKSAR Secretary of Justice Elsie Leung Oi-sie, on behalf of the
Chief Executive's Office, made an Introduction to Hong Kong
Reunification Bill which provides for the confirmation of
legislation approved by the PLC and the continuity of the legal
system and the civil service.
</P>
<P>
One of its major functions was to confirm the validity of the
bills which have been passed by the body before July 1, Leung
said.
</P>
<P>
There is no doubt about the validity of the laws passed prior
to the handover, but the confirmation process on July 1 will serve
as an added assurance, she told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The bill also endorses the appointment of judges of the Court
of Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the High Court, and
provides for the continuity of legal proceedings, criminal justice
system and administration of justice by stipulating that actions
launched before July 1 will remain valid after the date.
</P>
<P>
Another key part of the bill is to deal with the interpretation
on and after July 1 of laws previously in force in Hong Kong, for
the continuation of those laws and for the confirmation of certain
laws.
</P>
<P>
Leung invited PLC members to give their views for amendments to
the draft bill, which had been published on June 18 by the Chief
Executive's Office.
</P>
<P>
The Office will include the views in the blue bill to be
formally presented to the PLC on July 1 so that it can go through
all three readings in the early hours of the day, she said.
</P>
<P>
The four bills won unanimous support at today's plenary meeting
when they were read for the third time, bringing to 13 the total
number of bills passed before the handover.
</P>
<P>
They are the Immigration (Amendment)(No.3) Bill 1997, the Hong
Kong Court of Final Appeal (Amendment) Bill 1997, the Judicial
Service Commission (Amendment) Bill 1997 and the Oaths and
Declarations (Amendment) Bill 1997.
</P>
<P>
The first three were tabled by the Chief Executive's Office for
first and second readings on June 7 while the fourth one was
tabled on June 14.
</P>
<P>
The Immigration (Amendment) Bill seeks to provide for the
status of a permanent resident together with the right of abode in
the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, there are six categories of permanent residents
who have the right of abode in the HKSAR, as stipulated by Article
24 of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Other major parts of the bill include: to provide for the
circumstances in which the right of abode may be lost and the
right to land in Hong Kong after the loss of such right, to
provide for the transitional arrangements for those who are not of
Chinese nationality but are permanent residents of Hong Kong
before July 1, and to provide for the definitions (or their
amendments) of certain expressions.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal (Amendment) Bill seeks to
amend the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal Ordinance, enacted in
1995, by including the provision of Article 90 of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The Article provides that the Chief Justice of the Court of
Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the High Court of the HKSAR
shall be Chinese citizens who are permanent residents of the
Region with no right of abode in any foreign country.
</P>
<P>
The Judicial Service Commission (Amendment) Bill ensures the
smooth appointment of the first group of judges of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
At the HKSAR government inauguration and swearing-in ceremony
on July 1, permanent Judges of the Court of Final Appeal and
Judges of the High Court will take their oaths immediately after
the Chief Executive, principal officials, members of the Executive
Council and members of the PLC, according to a decision made by
the Preparatory Committee for the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Legally speaking, members of the Judicial Officers
Recommendation Commission (JORC), an independent body formed under
the Basic Law to make recommendations to the Chief Executive on
the appointments of judges, should have taken their oaths before
making such recommendations.
</P>
<P>
However, this arrangement is impossible on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances, the amendment bill includes a
transitional provision to ensure that the recommendations made by
the JORC can not be challenged simply because its members have not
taken their oaths prior to making the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The Oaths and Declarations (Amendment) Bill aims to implement
through local legislation the provision in Article 104 of the
Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Under the article, when assuming office, the Chief Executive,
principal officials, members of the Executive Council, members of
the PLC and judges and other members of the HKSAR judiciary must
swear to uphold the Basic Law and swear allegiance to the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The bill repeals the colonial oaths and formulated appropriate
oaths in accordance with the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
After the full sitting, a subcommittee was formed to scrutinize
the draft Reunification Bill, with Ambrose Lau as the chairman.
Members of the subcommittee met this afternoon with
representatives of the Chief Executive's Office.
</P>
<P>
At lunch time, the PLC Working Group on Administrative Matters
met to review the preliminary designs of the logo of the PLC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Officials to Be Trained in Silicon Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 21 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to promote high-tech
manpowers, the South Korean government plans to send 30 officials
to Silicon Valley, the center of U.S. venture businesses, over the
next three years.
</P>
<P>
"Now that the promotion of information-oriented venture
companies to help foster economic competitiveness has emerged as a
national priority, government officials themselves have to obtain
firsthand knowledge in order to formulate future policies," said
an official of the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, the ministry has decided to send a group of
30 officials including those from other agencies to Silicon Valley
until the year 2000, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The government will also set up an educational program at the San
Francisco-based high-tech industrial center to foster South Korean
entrepreneurs and would-be start-ups.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ministry plans to operate advisor groups to
help invigorate the nation's venture firms both at home and in
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
By linking up with prestigious universities from around the
region, the ministry will provide a training program for high-tech
start-ups and some 1,500 South Korean businessmen and technology
experts between now and the year 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
