<HEADLINE> Kenyan Official on Lifting of Ivory Trade Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The lifting of the ban on ivory
trade does not threaten the survival of the African elephant,
said Kenyan Wildlife Service Director David Western.
</P>
<P>
David Western said that although Kenya lost in the hotly
contested lifting of the ivory trade ban, it's happy that
international monitoring for illegal poaching continues to be in
force, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official made the remarks Friday on his arrival
from Harare, Zimbabwe, where he had attended the U.N. Convention
on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The rules are very stringent. The nations can only dispose of
their stockpiles after a 21-month moratorium," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Botswana won a proposal to sell their
ivory conditionally at the Harare meeting where Kenya and the
United States were probably the only nations opposed to the
trade.
</P>
<P>
However,"there was very strong African support for the
downlisting. And there was great deal of groundwork," said
Western.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's fear is that the resumption in trade threatens to
precipitate the wanton poaching that almost wiped out Africa's
elephant and rhino populations in the 1970s and 1980s until the
ban was imposed in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The decision at the CITES meeting was not exactly what kenya
wanted but also "definitely not what the southern African nations
proposed... it was a compromise," he said.
</P>
<P>
African nations are likely to meet in Nairobi in the next two
months to review the Harare decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
