<HEADLINE> Uganda: Egypt's Nile Water Quota Unchallenged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has cleared up doubts that some Nile basin countries are acting to
limit the flow of the river to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Arabic Al Ahram newspaper published
today, Museveni hailed cooperative relations between Egypt and his
country and said he seeks to tighten the ties.
</P>
<P>
Ruling out the possibility of reducing Cairo's share of Nile
River water, he said that Uganda has plenty of water as it hosts
the spring of the river.
</P>
<P>
"We receives more water than Egypt so there are no attempts to
diminish water reaching Egypt," he added.
</P>
<P>
As Ethiopia is considering building four dams along the Blue
Nile in addition to other water utilization works of other Nile
basin states, suspicions arise that Egypt's quota of water will be
lowered.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan president described the situation as just
"misunderstanding." He added that his country depends on the
rainfall for irrigation and the Nile water represents just a
reserve.
</P>
<P>
"All such fears are not correct," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Egyptian government also denied any contact
between Cairo and any Nile basin state to rearrange the water
share.
</P>
<P>
The only agreement in place on the Nile dates back to 1959,
under which Egypt has access to 55.5 billion cubic meters, or 99
percent, of its sweet water resources.
</P>
<P>
The Nile basin is home to Egypt, Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda,
Rwanda, Eritrea, Burundi, Kenya, Zaire and Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
