<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Provisional Legislature Almost Fulfills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers for the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) have fulfilled the bulk of
their pre-handover tasks as they wrapped up a series of 12
meetings in this southern Chinese city today.
</P>
<P>
The 60-member Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) ended its
last plenary meeting here today, passing the third reading of four
more bills. So far the interim legislature has endorsed 13 bills,
which are believed to be indispensable to the establishment of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Exactly six months have elapsed since December 21, 1996, when
the interim body was elected by a 400-strong Selection Committee,
which was also responsible for the selection of the first Chief
Executive of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
"The PLC was not a best option, but it was the best option
under the circumstances," said Rita Fan, president of the interim
body. The situation was that the "through train", namely, all the
60 legislators of the 1995 Legislative Council to remain in
session after July 1, 1997, was derailed by the unilateral action
taken by the British side. To avoid the legal vacuum after July 1,
it is necessary to form a tentative legislative body.
</P>
<P>
In respect for the British rule of Hong Kong before July 1,
1997, the PLC has held all its 12 plenary meetings in Shenzhen,
the Chinese city bordering Hong Kong, over the past six months.
</P>
<P>
The interim legislature had its president elected on January
25, 1997, and then set up two ad hoc groups -- one on rules of
procedure and the other on administrative matters, and based its
Secretariat in Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Starting from early April, the PLC passed 13 bills, which are
vital to the smooth operation of the HKSAR government after July
1, 1997. Four bills were passed in the third reading today,
including the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal (Amendment) Bill
1997, the Judicial Service Commission (Amendment) Bill 1997, the
Immigration (Amendment) (No. 3) Bill 1997 and the Oaths and
Declarations (Amendment) Bill 1997.
</P>
<P>
Nine other bills had already been endorsed at previous plenary
meetings of the PLC, including Holidays (1997 and 1998) Bill,
Regional Council (Amendment) Bill 1997, Urban Council (Amendment)
Bill 1997, District Boards (Amendment) Bill 1997, the Legislative
Council Commission (Amendment) Bill 1997, National Flag and
National Emblem Bill, Regional Flag and Regional Emblem Bill,
Public Order (Amendment) Bill 1997, and Societies (Amendment) Bill
1997.
</P>
<P>
The legislation approved by the PLC needs to be ratified on
July 1, and then submitted to the Chief Executive for consent
before they become laws.
</P>
<P>
The PLC also passed three motions in respective support of the
Transitional Budget between 1997 and 1998, the appointment of
Andrew IL Kwok-nang as the Chief Justice of the HKSAR Court of
Final Appeal (CFA), and the appointment of three permanent judges
of the CFA and the Chief Judge of the HKSAR High Court.
</P>
<P>
A blue bill, Hong Kong Reunification Bill 1997, is expected to
be gazetted and passed in all its three readings on July 1 to
ratify the 13 bills approved by the PLC.
</P>
<P>
A draft on the Reunification Bill 1997 has been published by
the HKSAR Chief Executive's Office. Apart from ratification of
legislation approved by the PLC, the draft bill also endorses the
appointment of the Chief Justice and judges of the HKSAR CFA and
the Chief Judge of the High Court.
</P>
<P>
It also refers to various transition-related subjects, such as
the interpretation and continuation of the laws already in force
in Hong Kong, the continuity of legal proceedings and the public
service, and the transfer of government assets and liabilities.
</P>
<P>
Elsie Leung Oi-sie, Secretary of Justice of the HKSAR, today
presented to the PLC a consultation paper, hoping to collect views
for amendment of the draft bill. A subcommittee under the PLC was
set up today to discuss the draft bill.
</P>
<P>
To introduce the draft bill to the PLC members at this moment is
to ensure the smooth passage of the Reunification Bill in the
small hours of July 1, 1997, according to the Secretary of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
After July 1, the PLC is expected to enact a law on the
election of the first HKSAR Legislative Council, which should be
established no later than June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The term of the PLC will not extend beyond June 30, 1998. PLC
President Rita Fan said: "When the first Legislative Council is
formed, the PLC will have fulfilled its historical task."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0110 </DOCNO>
