<HEADLINE> hkhk - Expatriates in Hong Kong Optimistic about Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is a highly
internationalized city with Chinese accounting for 95 percent of
the total residents and expatriates, five percent, according to
figures provided by the Census and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
Among the expatriates in Hong Kong are the Philippines,
Americans, Canadians, Britons, Thais, Japanese, Indians,
Australians and Malaysians, with Americans numbering 32,600,
Canadians, 28,200, Britons, 26,700 and Japanese, 21,500.
</P>
<P>
Of the local residents, 38.1 percent speak English, 1.8 percent
speak Philippines and 1.2 percent speak Japanese.
</P>
<P>
The expatriates in Hong Kong are optimistic about the future
after Hong Kong returns to China. They agree that post-handover
Hong Kong remains a 'investment paradise" for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
More than 95 percent of the British, American and Japanese
business people have expressed the intention of staying in Hong
Kong after the handover.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics up to mid-1996 provided by the Industry
Department, 2,300 foreign companies had set up offices in Hong
Kong, an increase of 12 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
This year, 8.4 percent more foreign companies are expected to
set up offices here, bringing the total number of foreign
companies with offices here to more than 2,500. 
</P>
</TEXT>
