<HEADLINE> E.Africa to Form Zero-Tariff Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, JUNE 21 (Xinhua) -- Three East African countries
planned to form a regional zero-tariff market in three years,
Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Francis Muthaura, Chief Executive of the
East African Co-operation Secretariat, as saying on Friday that
Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania were aiming at the zero-tariff market
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to the East African Development Strategy 1997-2000
paper adopted at a recent regional summit, the three countries
will establish a single market and investment area in the region
within the shortest time possible.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the priority of the strategy paper was the
development of the regional economic infrastructure like
transport, communications and energy.
</P>
<P>
Muthaura disclosed that his secretariat had already identified
some regional designated roads and rail projects and was seeking
financial support from outside.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that these projects would facilitate the free
movement of goods, people, service and capital within the East
African region.
</P>
<P>
The strategy paper underscores the need for political
co-operation among the three member states to prevent conflicts
within the region through open dialogues, he said.
</P>
<P>
Muthaura noted that some progresses had been made for regional
co-operation in the areas of policy harmonization such as
the establishment of a mechanism for co-operation of the capital
and securities market regulatory authorities and the formation of the
East African Business Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
