<HEADLINE> Kenyan Minister Calls on Western Media to Be Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Foreign Affairs Minister
Kalonzo Musyoka has called on the international media to give
both sides of information in reporting events of the eastern
African country.
</P>
<P>
Musyoka criticized the western media organizations for
attempting to " feed the world only with negative information",
the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"For example, Kenya is the most attractive tourism destination
in the world, but this is hardly highlighted," the Kenyan foreign
minister said while receiving a Time magazine delegation here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There is also much good going on in the country", he
continued, expressing the hope that the magazine would bring out
the truth about the country.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Kenya's national economic development, Musyoka
said that Kenya aims at reaching a seven percent gross domestic
product growth rate so as to acquire the status of an
industrialized nation by 2020.
</P>
<P>
Mark Simpson, Time's Middle East and Africa Regional Sales
Manager and the chief of the delegation, said that the magazine
would build Kenya's image by exercising balanced reportage.
</P>
