<HEADLINE> S.African Official Appeals for End to Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- South African Home Affairs
Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi Friday urged the government to take
immediate steps to stop the flood of illegal immigrants and
remove those already in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Pretoria on Friday,
Buthelezi warned that failure to curb illegal immigrants would
impoverish South Africa. If all illegal aliens were removed, the
country's unemployment problem would be closer to a solution, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi said the Aliens Control Act might be amended soon to
enact heavy penalties on people employing illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that around 2.5 to 4.1 million aliens are now
in South Africa, with some claiming the actual number as more
than eight million.
</P>
<P>
However, some cabinet members have reportedly suggested
illegal immigrants from neighboring states be treated leniently
as these countries supported the struggle against apartheid.
</P>
<P>
According to Buthelezi, the South African government's
decision last year to grant permanent residence to some citizens
of Southern African Development Community members had resulted in
200,000 applications.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 percent of the applications had so far been
approved, Buthelezi added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
