<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preparations for Forming HKSAR Government Well Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- On February 20 this year, the
State Council, based on the nomination by Tung Chee Hwa, first
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR), formally appointed 23 leading officials of the first
HKSAR government.
</P>
<P>
These officials will assume office on July 1 after Hong Kong
returns to China and the HKSAR is established.
</P>
<P>
Among the incumbent leading officials of the British Hong Kong
government, except one foreign citizen and one who is going to
retire soon, all have been appointed as leading officials of the
HKSAR government and will retain their current posts.
</P>
<P>
This has reflected the sincerity and resolution of the central
government to implement the HKSAR Basic Law and to maintain the
stability of the civil service in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Article 100 of the Basic Law stipulates that "public servants
serving in all Hong Kong government departments, including the
police department, before the establishment of the HKSAR, may all
remain in employment and retain their seniority with pay,
allowances, benefits and conditions of service no less favorable
than before."
</P>
<P>
According to this stipulation, after the founding of the HKSAR,
all its leading officials, including secretary and vice-secretary
of all departments, commissioner of the Independent Commission
Against Corruption, director of Audit, commissioner of Police,
director of Immigration and commissioner of Customs and Excise,
should be nominated by the SAR Chief Executive and appointed by
the Central People's Government.
</P>
<P>
Great efforts were made by Tung Chee Hwa in the course of
forming the first HKSAR government.
</P>
<P>
After being appointed last December by the central government
as the first Chief Executive of the HKSAR, Tung held a series of
meetings with more than 20 senior officials of the Hong Kong
government, and completed the nomination within two months.
</P>
<P>
The first senior official he met with was Anson Chan, Chief
Secretary of the Hong Kong government.
</P>
<P>
On the early morning of December 28 last year, Tung and Chan
had a breakfast meeting which lasted for about two hours. They
discussed a whole range of issues, including the stability and
transition of the civil service, assistance from the Hong Kong
government for the SAR Chief Executive, the Provisional
Legislative Council, and some other questions drawing attention of
the public.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the two walked out with smiling faces to
meet the reporters. Both described the meeting as "very useful and
constructive".
</P>
<P>
Tung told the reporters that the 180,000 civil servants are an
important foundation for Hong Kong's success, and that it was very
important to maintain the morale of the civil service and ensure
its smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that all the civil servants are of one mind, and are
working hard for Hong Kong's future," he said, "We all hope that
the return of Hong Kong will be smooth and successful."
</P>
<P>
He revealed that Chan had accepted his invitation to stay in
the government after the establishment of the SAR. "I am very
delighted," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the following one month, Tung held meetings with 21 other
senior officials of the Hong Kong government.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings, each of which lasted more than an hour,
Tung heard reports on the work of various departments, and
exchanged views with the officials on a series of policy-oriented
issues.
</P>
<P>
The issues include Hong Kong's finance, securities, trade,
public security, environmental planning, land supply,
transportation and their prospects.
</P>
<P>
Most of these senior public servants expressed the intention of
serving the SAR government, and none of them expressed worries
about whether they would retain their current posts.
</P>
<P>
As a result of painstaking efforts, on January 24 this year,
Tung announced the nimblest of the members of the first Executive
Council of the HKSAR, the top advisory body for the HKSAR Chief
Executive.
</P>
<P>
Later, he also submitted the namelist of the HKSAR leading
officials to the central government.
</P>
<P>
With the formation of the Executive Council and the appointment
of the SAR leading officials by the central authorities, the power
framework of the HKSAR has taken shape.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
