<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Provisional Legislature Passes Four Bills in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Four bills were adopted today by
the Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) which held its 12th plenary meeting
in this South China city.
</P>
<P>
They are the Immigration (Amendment)(No.3) Bill 1997, the Hong
Kong Court of Final Appeal (Amendment) Bill 1997, the Judicial
Service Commission (Amendment) Bill 1997 and the Oaths and
Declarations (Amendment) Bill 1997.
</P>
<P>
The first three bills were tabled by the Chief Executive's
Office for first and second readings on June 7 while the fourth
was tabled on June 14.
</P>
<P>
The four bills, along with nine other bills which had passed
the third reading at the PLC's previous meetings, still have to go
through a confirmation process and gain the Chief Executive's
consent in the early hours of July 1 to become laws.
</P>
<P>
The Immigration (Amendment) Bill seeks to provide for the
status of a permanent resident together with the right of abode in
the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, there are six categories of permanent residents
who have the right of abode in the HKSAR, as stipulated by Article
24 of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Other major parts of the bill include: to provide for the
circumstances in which the right of abode may be lost and the
right to land in Hong Kong after the loss of such right, to
provide for the transitional arrangements for those who are not of
Chinese nationality but are permanent residents of Hong Kong
before July 1, and to provide for the definitions (or their
amendments) of certain expressions.
</P>
<P>
An early legislation on the right of abode which practically
affects everyone in the HKSAR could allay people's concern, HKSAR
Secretary of Justice Elsie Leung Oi-sie told lawmakers when
presenting the bill on June 7.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal (Amendment) Bill seeks to
amend the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal Ordinance, enacted in
1995, by including the provision of Article 90 of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The Article provides that the Chief Justice of the Court of
Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the High Court of the HKSAR
shall be Chinese citizens who are permanent residents of the
Region with no right of abode in any foreign country.
</P>
<P>
The Judicial Service Commission (Amendment) Bill ensures the
smooth appointment of the first group of judges of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
At the HKSAR government inauguration and swearing-in ceremony
on July 1, permanent Judges of the Court of Final Appeal and
Judges of the High Court will take their oaths immediately after
the Chief Executive, principal officials, members of the Executive
Council and members of the PLC, according to a decision made by
the Preparatory Committee for the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Legally speaking, members of the Judicial Officers
Recommendation Commission (JORC), an independent body formed under
the Basic Law to make recommendations to the Chief Executive on
the appointments of judges, should have taken their oaths before
making such recommendations.
</P>
<P>
However, this arrangement is impossible on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances, the amendment bill includes a
transitional provision to ensure that the recommendations made by
the JORC can not be challenged simply because its members have not
taken their oaths prior to making the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The Oaths and Declarations (Amendment) Bill aims to implement
through local legislation the provision in Article 104 of the
Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Under the article, when assuming office, the Chief Executive,
principal officials, members of the Executive Council, members of
the PLC and judges and other members of the HKSAR judiciary must
swear to uphold the Basic Law and swear allegiance to the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The bill repeals the colonial oaths and formulated appropriate
oaths in accordance with the Basic Law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
