<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of crude
palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week mixed.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals market ended the week strong with June South
higher at 1,222.50 ringgit (about 489 U.S. dollars) against 1,220
ringgit (about 488 U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
However, players on the market were bewildered with the release
of bearish production and stocks figures by private crop
forecaster Ivan Wong who anticipated production to slip one
percent to 783,000 tons but stocks are expected to grow to 770,000
tons from the May figures of 711,841 tons released by Palm Oil
Registration and Licensing Authority (PORLA) and exports to slow
down to 615,000 tons from 662,606 tons.
</P>
<P>
The market was also affected by the release of lower exports
figures by a cargo surveyor, Societe Generale de Surveillance
(SGS), for the first 20 days in June at 369,000 tons from 384,000
tons for May 1-20.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to trend lower in quiet trading next
week as players were worried with the anticipated bearish market
in the intermediate term, market sources said.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) was traded
in tight range as gains were capped by losses of three-month tin
on the London Metal Exchange (LME) throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
The market ended the week three Sen lower to 13.83 ringgit
(about 5.532 U.S. dollars) per kg with an accumulated turnover for
the week rising to 487 tons from 480 tons last week.
</P>
<P>
The local metal market is expected to trend sideways in
volatile trading next week, a dealer said, adding any uptrend is
expected to be aided by the LME.
</P>
<P>
On the Malaysian rubber market this week, it was badly hit in
tandem with softer regional markets.
</P>
<P>
July RSS One lost six Sen to 276 Sen (about 110.4 U.S. cents)
per kg from 282 Sen (about 112.8 U.S. cents), while SMR 20 slipped
five Sen to 253.5 Sen (about 101.4 U.S. cents) per kg from 258.5
Sen (about 103.4 U. S. cents) last week.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market price indicator for June 19 stood at 205.37
Malaysian/Singapore cents (Sen) per kg from 207.30 cents (Sen) per
kg on June 18.
</P>
<P>
Five day moving average was at 208.62 cents (Sen) compared with
209.81 cents (Sen).
</P>
<P>
Players are expected to sell their positions next week as they
are frustrated on the current rubber prices, as well as to avoid
further losses as buyers are waiting for lower prices, dealers
said, adding "with no demand, the market plunged further."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
