<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former US Chamber of Commerce Chairman Calls for Permanent MFN to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China should be granted permanent
most-favored-nation (MFN) trade status by the United States, said
James McGregor, former chairman of the US Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
In an interview here Friday with Xinhua, he added that the
disputes and misunderstandings between the two countries should
not affect China's permanent MFN.
</P>
<P>
McGregor, who is Vice-President (China) of Dow Jones &AMP; Company,
Inc., pointed out that MFN is normal trading rights, and "we
should focus on disputes and misunderstandings between the two
countries in a much clearer way with one issue at a time, instead
of throwing every dispute together under MFN."
</P>
<P>
McGregor called the annual debate over China's MFN a "useless
debate," and stressed this debate has hindered long-term
cooperative plans between business people of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
US policy-makers should be aware that China and some other
developing countries need time to develop, McGregor said, adding
"the progress in China should be measured against what it used to
be, not compared to a fully developed country."
</P>
<P>
US President Bill Clinton announced the decision last May to
extend China's MFN for another year. And the US House Ways and
Means Committee has recently voted in support of Clinton's
decision.
</P>
<P>
McGregor, who has lived in China for 10 years, expressed the
hope that more US congressmen would come to visit China and see
it for themselves. "There is a big gap between their view on China
and the real situation there," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, in the last 12 months, about 20 percent of
the US congress members visited China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
