<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Warn of Clashes in Nablus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Palestinians have warned of the
likelihood of serious clashes in the West Bank town of Nablus
today if Israeli forces try to prevent a planned protest gathering
in the city, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The gathering has been called by the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) and opposition groups to protest last week's
United States' decision to recognize Jerusalem as Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian security forces have informed their Israeli
counterpart that "they could not guarantee their own ability" to
prevent Palestinian demonstrators from entering the
Israeli-controlled Joseph Tomb area in the city.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals in Nablus have reportedly been put on an emergency
stand-by footing, as the Israeli army has been alerted in the
readiness for any possible clashes with the Palestinian
protesters.
</P>
<P>
Violent confrontations erupted in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip following last week's U.S. Congress resolution recognizing
Jerusalem as Israel's undivided capital.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives also voted to set aside 100
million U.S. dollars for moving the U.S. Embassy in Israel from
Tel Aviv to Jerusalem in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, who see East Jerusalem as the capital of
their future state, sharply criticized the resolution, which they
said would hurt the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. congressional resolution about Jerusalem was also
taken by Palestinians as implicit U.S. support for Israel's stand
to create facts on the ground prior to the final status
negotiations which will settle the issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio today quoted Israeli army Central Command Uzi
Dayan as saying that eight Israeli soldiers were lightly injured
in the week of violent confrontations with Palestinian protesters
in the West Bank town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at least 150 Palestinians were wounded, some of
them seriously, by rubber bullets and tear gas fired by the
Israeli soldiers to disperse the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
Dayan, who described the situation as tense, added that the
Israeli security forces were prepared to deal with the
possibility that the violent confrontations could spread.
</P>
<P>
He also accused the Palestinian police of not acting to prevent
the Palestinian protesters from reaching the line of the Jewish
community in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Israel security forces blamed the PNA for
"encouraging" the current clashes between the two sides, but the
Palestinians categorically denied the allegation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
