<HEADLINE> Research on Dunhuang Art Thriving in Hangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- This capital of Zhejiang Province
in east China has become one of the centers of study of the grotto
art, Buddhist aesthetics, music and dance, medicine, history,
language, geology and other aspects of Dunhuang, thanks to local
researchers.
</P>
<P>
Dunhuang is located in northwest China in Gansu province, where
there are some 500 grottoes that were carved from the 4th to the
14th centuries, more than 2,000 statues, 40,000 sq.m. of wall
frescoes, and 40,000 to 50,000 other relics.
</P>
<P>
The Dunhuang Research Institute in Zhejiang has conducted many
research projects and has become the leading provincial research
center after Gansu and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
A group of colleges and universities in the province have
established their own Dunhuang research institutes since the
1980s, and there is an association of Dunhuang studies.
</P>
<P>
Local researchers have written many papers on Dunhuang studies
and published a number of academic works, and there are plans for
a 30-million-word collection of documents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
