<HEADLINE> India to Investigate Sinking of Foreign Vessel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 21 (Xinhua)-- India's Merchantile Marine
Department and Calcutta Port Trust (CPT) would make an inquiry
into Thursday's sinking of Cargo ship MV Green Opal in a river
near the country's Calcutta's port.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry would ascertain the cause behind the sinking of the
vessel which hit a LASH barge, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The vessel belonged to Seoul-based Management Company Ltd. and
was carrying 9,000 tons of steel from India.
</P>
<P>
All the 20 crew members of the ship were rescued. A team of
marine officers including CPT pilots have left for the spot to
explore the possibility for movement of ships in and out of
Kidderpore and Calcutta docks in the country, which remained
suspended after the accident.
</P>
<P>
The owners of the ship have been asked to lift the sunk vessel
from the water as early as possible to help resume services at the
two docks.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Diamond Shippers, agent of the foreign
liner, has said that the bottom portion of the vessel was severely
damaged and it was difficult to lift it from the water.  
</P>
