<HEADLINE> Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- External and internal stability
in Nepal's economy has promoted investment and economic activities
in the country in the first 10 months of the current fiscal year
ending July 14, Nepal Rastra Bank said.
</P>
<P>
In a press released on Nepal's macroeconomic situation, Nepal
Rastra Bank, the country's central bank, said that while inflation
has dropped considerably this year, the growth rate of government
resources has exceeded that of the expenditure, resulting in a
significant reduction in the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the government account has recorded a cash surplus
amounting to 130 million rupees (about 2.3 million U.S. dollars)
this year as against the overdraft of 1.71 billion rupees (about
29 million U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange reserve level with the banking sector has
been sufficient to cover the current import requirement of six
months, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Total exports this year rose by 14.7 percent compared with 9.9
percent last year. Imports surged by 27.9 percent compared with
22.9 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the country's total foreign trade registered a
rise of 25.2 percent to 97.82 billion rupees (about 1.7 billion
U.S. dollars) this year as against a 20 percent increase to 78.15
billion rupees (about 1.4 billion U.S. dollars) during the same
10-month period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
