<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) market closed the week stronger with the Composite
Index (CI) up 19.16 points to 1,097.54.
</P>
<P>
The broader Emas Index also increased 2.29 points to 308.69
while the Industrial Index jumped 28.18 points to 2,092.85 during
the week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Second Board Index gained 6.18 points to 575.92.
</P>
<P>
The strong retracement was aided by an impressive broad money
supply growth as at end-April 1997, which grew 19.7 percent from
end-March growth of 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
Main board turnover improved to 923.215 million shares valued
at 5.650 billion ringgit (about 2.26 billion U.S. dollars) from
908.585 million stocks worth 4.957 billion ringgit (about 1.9828
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Second Board volume inflated to 341.616 million stocks worth
3.855 billion ringgit (about 1.542 billion U.S. dollars) from
230.536 million shares valued at 2.809 billion ringgit (about
1.1236 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals increased to 181.781 million stocks valued at
1.265 billion ringgit (about 506 million U.S. dollars) from
160.937 million shares worth 1.437 billion ringgit (about 574.8
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Two counters entered the Second Board's list this week.
</P>
<P>
T. H. Hin Corporation made its debut on Monday at 8.05 ringgit
(about 3.22 U.S. dollars) with 5.25 ringgit (about 2.1 U.S.
dollars) premium above its offer price of 2.80 ringgit (about 1.12
U.S. dollars). The manufacturer and distributor of gas cookers
ended the week at 7.90 ringgit (about 3.16 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Len Cheong Holding entered the Second Board's list on Friday at
6.30 ringgit (about 2.52 U.S. dollars) for a 4.30 ringgit (about
1.72 U.S. dollars) premium over its offer price of 2.00 ringgit
(about 80 U.S. cents). The manufacturer and marketer of rubberwood
furniture ended the week at 6.70 ringgit (about 2.68 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Top ten volume leaders this week were Renong which added 12 sen
to 3.48 ringgit, Sriwani Holdings up 75 sen to 6.10 ringgit, Eden
Enterprises surging 1.55 ringgit to 7.55 ringgit, Samanda soaring
2.60 ringgit to 22.0 ringgit, Olympia perking 19 sen to 2.18
ringgit, Suria Capital dipping 19 sen to 2.56 ringgit, Pembinaan
YCS up 2.50 ringgit to 15.20 ringgit, Isuta Holdings plunging 4.50
ringgit to 12.20 ringgit, Ekran rising 30 sen to 5.30 ringgit and
Asian Pac Holdings down nine sen to 2.20 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Renong saw 46.133 million shares traded, Sriwani 32.906 million
shares, Eden 32.487 million shares, Samanda 30.322 million shares,
Olympia 23.293 million shares, Suria 20.322 million shares, YCS
19.382 million shares, Isuta 19.032 million shares, Ekran 16.623
million shares and Asian Pac 15.678 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Consumer products accounted for 78.621 million shares traded,
industrial products 146.991 million shares, construction 106.046
million shares, trading/services 251.242 million shares,
infrastructure 11.918 million shares, finance 92.897 million
shares, hotels 9.529 million shares, properties 123.915 million
shares, plantations 41.156 million shares, mining 2.400 million
shares, trusts 412,500 shares, closed-end fund 2.040 million
shares and loan stocks 14.480 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Share prices are expected to firm further next week, dealers
said, adding if the market could burst through the CI 1,105
resistance next week it could edge higher to try the next
break-out points of 1,132.
</P>
<P>
A possible interest rate cut due to the slower growth is
expected to lead to capital flowing back into the stock market.
</P>
</TEXT>
