<HEADLINE> Handover-Related Press Commentaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The following is the gist of
some handover-related commentaries carried by the local press
today.
</P>
<P>
Ta Kung Pao today carries a commentary to stress the important
role of Hong Kong's civil servants.
</P>
<P>
The commentary says that the 180,000 civil servants constitute
a high-quality and efficient contingent which is a treasure and
the mainstay for future Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It says that from July 1 on, the 180,000 civil servants are
expected to continue their work for the government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) and they will face a
new task and new situation after the handover.
</P>
<P>
The civil servants should not worry about their future, the
commentary says, noting that the Basic Law guarantees the
stability of the civil service.
</P>
<P>
It calls on the civil servants to unite under the Basic Law and
to resist the dissension sowed by those with ulterior motives.
</P>
<P>
The commentary says that Hong Kong people have full confidence
in the civil servants who are expected to contribute to the
implementation of the "One Country, Two Systems" principle and to
Hong Kong's stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po in its editorial today notes the upward trend on the
Hong Kong stock market with the Hang Seng Index surging 647 points
to 15,154 and the turnover reaching 26.5 billion HK dollars
Friday.
</P>
<P>
It says that the records set at the Hong Kong stock market show
overseas funds are flowing into Hong Kong's stock market and one
of the factors is related to Hong Kong's imminent return to China.
</P>
<P>
It cites a report issued by the Standard &AMP; Poor, a well-known
risk and credit rating agency, which expressed its optimism about
Hong Kong's economic and credit strength after Hong Kong's
handover.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that with the closer tie between Hong Kong and
the mainland after the handover, Hong Kong's economy will see
further increase.  
</P>
</TEXT>
