<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves $174 Mln Stand-by Credit for Uruguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) today approved a 21-month stand-by credit for Uruguay
equivalent to some 174 million U.S. dollars, in support of the
government's 1997-98 economic program.
</P>
<P>
But the government of Uruguay does not intend to make drawings
under the stand-by credit, and will treat it as precautionary.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay's 1997-98 economic program seeks to reduce inflation to
single-digit levels by the end of 1998 in an environment of
sustained output and employment growth and to achieve a viable
external position. The program aims at real GDP growth of at least
3 percent in 1997 and 3 percent in 1998, a reduction in the rate
of inflation to 14-17 percent by the end of this year, and a
further strengthening of the international reserve position.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay joined the IMF in March 1946. Its quota in the IMF is
about 314 million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF credit
currently totals about 3 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
