<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consultation Paper on Reunification Bill Presented To Provisional Legislature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A consultation paper on
Reunification Bill 1997 was today presented to the Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) here in the southern Chinese city of Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The Reunification Bill, to be gazetted and passed through all
its three readings on July 1, 1997, aims to ratify all bills
passed by the interim legislature before June 30 and to deal with
various transition-related matters.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Justice Leung Oi-sie presented to the 60-member
PLC a consultation document, entitled "Introduction to Hong Kong
Reunification Bill 1997". A draft bill was published by the HKSAR
Chief Executive's Office on June 18.
</P>
<P>
Leung said that the Chief Executive's Office will collect views
for amendments of the draft bill so that a blue bill can be
gazetted and passed through all its three readings on July 1.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the 12th PLC's plenary meeting today, the
Secretary of Justice said: "Legislative step is required to
complete the law-making process for the ordinances which have been
passed by the PLC prior to July 1, 1997 and to deal with various
transition-related matters."
</P>
<P>
Upon the establishment of the HKSAR, the laws that have been
passed shall be ratified, reported to the Chief Executive for
signature, proclaimed for implementation so as to complete the
legislative procedure, according to Leung.
</P>
<P>
She stressed: "There is no doubt about the validity of the laws
passed prior to July 1, 1997. However, to make assurances doubly
sure, confirmation of the laws on July 1 will remove any doubt as
to the validity of these laws."
</P>
<P>
Besides, the draft bill endorses the appointment of the Chief
Justice and Judges of the Court of Final Appeal, and the Chief
Judge of the High Court.
</P>
<P>
It also refers to the interpretation and continuation of the
laws already in force in Hong Kong, the continuity of legal
proceedings and in the public service, the transfer of government
assets and liabilities, and the confirmation of the Appropriation
Bill.
</P>
<P>
Leung said that to introduce the draft bill to the PLC at this
moment is to ensure the smooth passage of the Reunification Bill
in the small hours of July 1, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
