<HEADLINE> hkhk-Interview: Secretary of Education and Manpower on Future Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He firmly believes the return of Hong Kong to the motherland
will surely help increase the cooperation and exchanges in
education between Hong Kong and the interior area.
Wong holds that teachers are the educational workers at the
frontline, and their attainment and integrity will have an impact
on their students and, therefore, more work should be done to
raise the teachers' competence, enhance their advanced training
and raise their status. Meanwhile, close attention should be paid
to the role of school masters. He said that education of a school
can be run well only with the help of an able and creative school
head.
</P>
<P>
His in-depth understanding of Hong Kong's education system leads
to his belief that Hong Kong now has a contingent of dedicated and
well-disciplined teachers whose relationship with the school
leadership is very close.
Hong Kong has long introduced a nine-year free, compulsory
education, and people have been provided with greater access to
college education. At present, 15 schools are added each year to
cope with the growth in the number of students. Wong pledged his
efforts in running the schools better still, so as to bring up and
train more talents for Hong Kong's future development.
Furthermore, he attached importance to advanced training. Noting
that the present era is one for the continuous growth of
information and science and technology, he said that the
government of the Hong Kong SAR will work out matro-strategic
plans in this regard so that employees will have more advanced
training and retraining to increase their competence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
