<DOCNO> XIE19970621.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Urge Stabilizing Thai Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Foreign chambers of commerce in
Thailand have urged the new Thai finance minister, Thanong Bidaya,
to make stabilizing the baht his first priority, a move which
could pave the way for a reduction of interest rates.
</P>
<P>
They also urged the six-party coalition government to focus on
the country's economic problems, not internal squabbling, to
restore foreign investor confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
They made their urges on Friday at a meeting with Commerce
Minister Narongchai Akrasanee, who resigned on Thursday but was
re-appointed to the same portfolio on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mark Israelsen, president of the American Chamber of Commerce,
said that recent political turmoil involving ministers in charge
of economic matters, has discouraged foreign investors from
further investing in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the new finance minister ensure the baht
stability.
</P>
<P>
Thanong, president of the Military Bank, was appointed on
Friday to replace Amnuay Viravan, who resigned on Thursday under
pressure of coalition government parties.
</P>
<P>
Requesting the new finance minister to stick to existing
measures, Israelsen said soon after the pressure on the baht
eases, it should be possible to lower interest rates to boost the
weak economy.
</P>
<P>
Investors are wailing for the new finance minister to make a
policy statement, Israelsen said.
</P>
<P>
He added that investors believe in the long-term economic
fundamentals of Thailand but the government needs to demonstrate
an ability to tackle economic problems with sound policies.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar held earlier this week, some economic analysts
believed that the baht is 10 percent over-valued.
</P>
<P>
Currently the baht is pegged to a basket of currencies
dominated by the U.S. dollar with around 80 percent. The fixed
exchange rate regime has been vulnerable to foreign speculators'
attacks, in particular, since this year.
</P>
<P>
Nimit Nontapunthawat, senior vice president of the Bangkok Bank
Research Department, said the baht should be allowed to move more
to better cope with the country's financial liberalization policy.
</P>
<P>
Supat Julaanatatham, a lecturer at the Economics Faculty of
Thammasat University, said the fixed exchange rate mechanism will
push interest rates up in order to defend the baht from
speculative attacks.
</P>
<P>
This year, the baht has come under periodic attacks from
foreign speculators looking for profits.
</P>
<P>
Supat noted that economic recovery is still far away as long as
interest rates remain high in defense of the baht.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's interest rates are currently the highest in the
region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
