<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prospects Bright for Australia-HK Economic Cooperation: Australian Businessman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- "For us, what happens on June 30
is going to be the same as what happens on July 1, and our
business will be done the same way," said Alfred Chown, chairman
of the Australian Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong while
commenting on the upcoming return of Hong Kong to China.
</P>
<P>
With more than 1,100 members, the Australian Chamber of
Commerce is the second largest foreign chamber in Hong Kong, next
to the American chamber.
</P>
<P>
"Australian business in Hong Kong is very strong, and Hong Kong
is the largest outpost of Australian business outside Australia,"
Chown noted.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are over 700 Australian businesses registered
in Hong Kong, and the number of Australians in Hong Kong is close
to 30,000. Last year, the total volume of Hong Kong-Australian
trade reached 3.9 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Describing the resumption of exercise of sovereignty over Hong
Kong by the Chinese government as a major event worth grand
celebrations, Chown noted that the international business
community is very happy with the smooth development of the Hong
Kong handover and transition.
</P>
<P>
"After July 1, I believe that the relationship between
Australia and Hong Kong will go on well, and the prospects for
their economic cooperation and trade are quite good," he said.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that there is a wide scope for economic
cooperation and trade between Australia, Hong Kong and the
interior area of China, and sectors like food, construction
materials, cosmetics, communications, medicine, information and
service could produce great business opportunities for the
Australians.
</P>
<P>
"After the handover, the chamber will continue what it is
doing now, trying to facilitate trade between Hong Kong,
Australia and China's interior area, and helping businessmen and
traders from Australia to come here to do business," he said.
</P>
<P>
The chamber will also try to share information, introduce
people to each other, and lobby the government for policies that
benefit the Sino-Australian relationship, he added.
</P>
<P>
Looking forward to the future of Hong Kong, Chown said that the
return to China will give Hong Kong "a lot of room for growth".
But while maintaining a high degree of autonomy, Hong Kong must
further integrate its economy with that of the Chinese interior
area if it wants to seek greater prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"From the economic perspective, Hong Kong's return to China is
like a fantastic star joining a very good football team," he said.
"If the star and the team work very well together, with the skills
of the star and the talents of the other players, they can walk on
to be a very very strong team."
</P>
<P>
Like many other Australian businessmen, Chown, who started to
serve as chairman of the Australian chamber in 1995, owned
businesses in both Hong Kong and the interior area.
</P>
<P>
Chown expressed strong appreciation for the "one country, two
systems" principle the Chinese government adopted for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very good policy and, so long as it is carried out
in full, Hong Kong will have a great and fantastic future," Chown
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
