<HEADLINE> Leaders of G7, Russia Open Summit in Denver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Denver, Colorado, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the seven
Western industrialized countries and Russia opened their summit
meeting here today to discuss the major economic and political
issues.
</P>
<P>
Hosted by U.S. President Bill Clinton, the summit was attended
by leaders from France, Britain, Germany, Italy, Canada, Japan and
the president of The European Council.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin was also present at the opening
reception of the annual summit and will participate in the meeting
from the beginning for the first time rather than being relegated
to a subsidiary role of joining the summit after G7 economic
agenda is completed.
</P>
<P>
Major economic issues on the agenda of the 23rd summit are
globalization, macro-economy in the U.S. and Europe, promoting
economic development in Africa, integrating Russia into the global
economy, reducing the threats to the global financial market and
the retiring baby boomer in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The summit opened at a time when the U.S. economy is on a
modest but stable expansion while some European nations including
Germany are in difficulties with high unemployment and huge
government deficit.
</P>
<P>
In a scene-setting speech here on Thursday, Clinton urged G7
industrailized nations to follow the U.S. example and strengthen
the economies by abandoning "old ideas" and cutting the
deficit. The G7 leaders will have something to agree upon on the
macro-economical issues.
</P>
<P>
There are also matters at odds between the leaders of seven
Western industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto has said that Japan
wanted assurances from G7 leaders that Russia would be kept out of
key meeting on financial and macro-economic matters.
</P>
<P>
The question of how to bring about growth and stability in
Africa will be featured during the summit and the U.S. and France
will express their different prescriptions on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit meeting will end on June 22 after issuing
a long-prepared communique. The summit is also a good chance for
the leaders of the eight countries to meet for talks on the issues
concerning to both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
