<HEADLINE> Liaoning Reshaping State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province has decided to create a two-billion-yuan fund to write
off the bad debts of local state economy, in a recent move to
optimize the assets structure of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is one of the several key industrial bases of China,
and local large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises account
for one tenth of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
However, many local state-owned enterprises have been losing
money since the country launched its market economy campaign.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say that the Liaoning provincial government
will take measures to support the ailing state-owned enterprises
to upgrade their technology, introduce overseas investment, and
list themselves on the stock market in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a total of 200,000 workers will be laid off from the
state sector.
</P>
<P>
The province will raise funds for pension insurance, and nearly
96 percent of workers in the state-owned enterprises will be
insured against unemployment risks.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the average assets and liability ratio of the
state-owned enterprises will be lowered by three to five
percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
