<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Motor Voters Didn't Motor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 20 (Xinhua) -- About 3.4 million Americans
signed up to vote by making use of a law enabling them to register
by mail or while renewing a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
But these so called "motor voters" didn't motor to the polls.
</P>
<P>
Turnout for last year's presidential election dropped despite a
record-high registration, said a Federal Election Commission (FEC)
study.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 73 percent of those old enough to vote were registered
and only 49 percent cast ballots, the FEC said. Four years
earlier, the comparable figures were 71 percent registered with 55
percent voting.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, supporters said, the national motor voter law
passed in 1993 was effective.
</P>
<P>
The law requires most states to let people register at the
local driver's license bureau, when applying for welfare or
disability benefits, and by mail.
</P>
<P>
The change seems to give neither Democratic or Republican
candidates an edge, although the number of people registered as
independents or third-party voters has risen.
</P>
<P>
For President Bill Clinton's second election, the 49 percent
turnout of citizens old enough to vote was the lowest since Calvin
Coolidge was chosen in 1924.
</P>
<P>
The number of registered voters increased by 9.2 million from
1992. The FEC attributed a little over one-third of the increase
to the new law. Most of the rest came from population growth.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four states and the District of Columbia are covered by
the National Voter Registration Act.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
