<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improving Ecology Helps Northeast China Grain Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Improving the ecology in China's
Heilongjiang province in the past several years has helped
increase the province's grain output, with a yearly average
increase of 10.5 percent in the past seven years, 7 percent more
than the country's average in that time.
</P>
<P>
The province accounted for 19 percent of China's grain output
increase, making it the largest grain producing base in China.
</P>
<P>
It has 130 million mu (8.66 million hectare) of arable land but
used to suffer badly from soil erosion and declining soil
fertility because of over-use.
</P>
<P>
But in the 1990s, an ecological improvement drive was begun,
resulting in 858 model ecological agriculture zones, farm shelter
belts, and a reduction in the pollutants on farmland. Average
grain output in Baiquan county had dropped significantly because
of soil erosion and the worsening environment, but now the grain
production has doubled, after 133,000 hectare of eroded land was
put under control and 72,000 hectare forested.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 2 million hectares of eroded land has been
put under control, and provincial forest coverage has gone from
37.5 percent in 1990 to 41.9 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
