<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Despite Venezuela's international currency reserves
rising 5.94 percent to 16.147 billion U.S. dollars in the first
five months of this year compared with the same period of 1996,
its economic growth was low, the country's Central Bank announced
today.
</P>
<P>
The reserves have been growing moderately despite the rate of
exchange stabilization, which has also registered an acceptable
increase thanks to the bank's monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's textile industry posted a 3.4 million
dollar trade surplus in the first quarter of 1997, a 90 percent
contraction compared to the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The sharp reduction drew grave concern from authorities, who
urged control on imports, which rose 41.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The World Bank authorized a 28 million dollar
loan to Panama for its social investment project initiated by the
Social Emergency Fund of the country.
</P>
<P>
This project, to be implemented from 1997 to 2001, will be
directed at community work with the support of the Panamanian
government, which will contribute 10,037,143 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Social Emergency Fund director Geraldo Solis said the project
is expected to benefit 283,437 poor people and create 31,873 jobs.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The Bank of Foreign Trade of Colombia
(Bancoldex) allotted a credit of 100 million dollars for the
construction of infrastructure, including bridges between Colombia
and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Bancoldex President Gabriel Turbay Marulanda, said it is
planned to speed the traffic in the Venezuelan department of Norte
de Santander and the Colombian state of Tachira, where 80 percent
of bilateral commerce transits.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean copper output by Escondida first five
months of the year was 406,000 tons, up 18.8 percent over the same
period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Its fine copper output was 119,000 metric tons in May.
</P>
<P>
The copper deposit yielded 841,000 metric tons last year,
accounting for 26 percent of the national copper production and
making it the biggest copper producer in the world.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan gross domestic product increased
4.2 percent in the first quarter of this year against the same
period of 1996, and accumulated an annual rise of 5.6 percent,
according to the Central Bank of Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The growth of the economy was led by commerce, which rose 14.8
percent, followed by agriculture and livestock with 9.0 percent,
manufacturing industry (excluding oil refining) 3.2 and
construction 3.2.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Brazilian insurance market registered in the
first four months of the year an income of 5.6 billion dollars, up
 20.9 percent over the same period of 1996, said the Finance
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Health insurance grew more than 41.6 percent to 1.1 billion
dollars with life insurance rising 18.4 percent to 1.030 billion
dollars, and motor vehicle insurance 22.76 percent to 720 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ministry added that from January to April the payment of
indemnities rose to 3.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
