<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Sees Clear Path to Paris Club </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, June 20 (Xinhua) -- All the obstacles facing
Russia's entry into the Paris Club have been removed, said a
Russian spokesman here today.
</P>
<P>
"All questions have been solved on Russia's entry into the Paris
Club as a creditor nation," said Sergi Yastrzhembsky, spokesman
for Russian President Boris Yeltsin. He was speaking after a
meeting between United States President Bill Clinton and Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
During their summit in Helsinki in March, Clinton promised
Yeltsin to help Russia join the Paris Club this year.
</P>
<P>
Before their meeting today, Clinton told reporters that Russia
will be "a partner with the other members in trying to help
promote the global economic growth by relieving the burden of the
debt on developing questions."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Clinton discussed European security issues, arms
control and Russia's integration into the global economy during
their meeting today, hours before the opening of the Summit of
Eight in Denver.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told Clinton that he would not go to Madrid to attend
the special summit of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO), which will focus on the alliance's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky told reporters that Clinton expressed his
"complete understanding" about the motives of Yeltsin's decision
of not going to Madrid.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously the decision demonstrates that Russia continues to
oppose the NATO's expansion," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
But he added that Russia will be represented at the summit in
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
On arms control, the spokesman said there was no progress.
Negotiations on amending the Conventional Forces Treaty in Europe
were "difficult" and could not be completed before the Madrid
summit, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky added that the talks on the treaty should be
"viewed together with the Russia-NATO Founding Act." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
