<HEADLINE> World Bank to Provide Big Credits for 2 African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today announced
the approval of big credits totaling 253.9 million U.S. dollars
for projects in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The first credit of some 125 million dollars is earmarked for
Kenya's energy sector reform and power development project
designed to assist the government of Kenya in formulating and
implementing major policy and institutional reforms aimed to
create an efficient and environmentally sustainable energy sector
and to support investment needed to meet power demand.
</P>
<P>
The other credit of 128.9 million dollars equivalent will be
used to help Tanzania's structural adjustment program aimed at
backing the government's efforts to achieve macrostability, growth
and poverty reduction through a reform of public expenditure
policies, efficient provision of social services and accelerated
privatization of parastatals.
</P>
<P>
Both credits will be channeled through the International
Development Association, the World Bank's concessionary lending
wing for developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
