<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Puerto Ricans Criticize US New Act on Puerto Rico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- A bill of the United States
on Puerto Rico's status was widely criticized by the Puerto Ricans
at the Special Committee on Decolonization here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bill, known as the Puerto Rico political status act, would
provide for a plebiscite on the political status of Puerto Rico to
be held some time before December 31, 1998, in which the people
would choose between statehood, sovereignty or continuing the
current status of a self-governing commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
A petitioner from the Committee Puerto Rico '98 said the bill
excluded 2.8 million Puerto Ricans living in the United States and
others around the world from voting in the plebiscite, while
foreign-born United States citizens who lived or temporarily
resided in Puerto Rico would be permitted to vote.
</P>
<P>
Iris B. Alfonso, of the United States-based National Congress
for Puerto Rican Rights, said, "We are a colony of the United
States and a territory which, to this day, has not exercised its
right to self-determination. The United States has not complied
with the procedures outlined in the 1960 General Assembly
Declaration on Decolonization."
</P>
<P>
Caros Vizcarrondo Irizarry, of the Puerto Rican Autonomy
Commission, said the U.S. bill called for a status plebiscite
which was a violation of international law and rejected the
legitimacy of the present commonwealth status of the island.
</P>
<P>
Several petitioners said the United Nations should supervise
any plebiscite on the political future of Puerto Rico. Other
petitioners said any dispute over Puerto Rico's status should be
determined by the International Court of Justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
