<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Promises to Detarget Missiles From Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin today promised Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
that Russia will detarget its missiles from Japan for better
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin made the promise during a meeting with Hashimoto here
early today before leaders of the G-7 members and Russia open
their three-day summit.
</P>
<P>
"The president told the prime minister that there are former
Soviet missiles still targeted at Japan and that time has come to
take Japan off the targets," a Japanese Foreign Ministry spokesman
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said that Japan needs to know more
details about the promise.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to a new plan proposed by Japan to
expand its investment in Russia. Yeltsin promised to improve his
country's environment for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
"Japan wants to normalize relations with Russia fully," the
Japanese spokesman said, adding, "It will take some time to
conclude this issue."
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told Yeltsin that Russia strengthened its relations
with Western European countries in the West, and "in the East,
Russia can cooperate with Japan," according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Japan, which has a territorial dispute with Russia, opposes
Moscow's full participation in the G-7 summit meetings, which are
divided into political and economic sectors.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said Thursday that he would seek assurances from
other G-7 leaders that Russia would continue to be excluded from
the group's meetings on financial and macro-economic matters.
Russia was not yet ready to join the G-7, and it will probably
take some time for "full integration of Russia into the
international financial system," said a Japanese spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who is excluded from the one-hour-long financial
meeting Saturday during the summit, came to Denver with a hope
that the G-7 will turn into a club of G-8.
</P>
<P>
The G-7, which was initiated in 1975, comprises France, Japan,
the U.S., Britain, Canada, Italy and Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
