<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Publishes Guidelines for Euro Accounting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, has published guidelines to
facilitate a smooth and orderly changeover to the use of the euro
in company accounts.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines, prepared by the commission' services in close
cooperation with EU member states and the accounting profession,
aim to help national accounting standard setting authorities and
people compiling and using accounts throughout the EU to prepare
for the drawing up of financial statements in euros.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines confirm that the introduction of the euro will
not require any additional EU accounting legislation or amendment
of existing accounting directives.
</P>
<P>
"These guidelines give practical and comprehensive advice to
standard setters and those that draw up and use company accounts,"
said EU Single Market Commissioner Mario Monti, "and so help them
to ensure a smooth changeover to euro."
</P>
<P>
Yves-Thibault de Silguy, EU commissioner for economic, monetary
and financial affairs, said that these guidelines "fit into the
Commission's overall strategy for EMU preparations."
</P>
<P>
The Amsterdam European Council meeting, which was held on June
16 and 17, confirmed the legal framework for the introduction of
the euro, which is scheduled to be launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
