<HEADLINE> US Deficit Through May Down 40 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. federal budget deficit
went down 40 percent so far in fiscal 1997 compared with a year
ago, a report from the U.S. Treasury Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The department noted the budget deficit through May totaled
65.4 billion dollars, down from 108.4 billion dollars during the
first eight months of fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
After hitting a record 290.4 billion dollars in fiscal 1992,
the federal deficit steadily declined through last year. The
Clinton administration has forecast a 125.6 billion dollar deficit
in the year ending September 30, still up from 107.4 billion
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the Congressional Budget Office and many private
economists project the imbalance will decline even more this fiscal
year, in part because of the strong economy. Actually, tax receipts
resulting from income and profit gains helped produce the largest
monthly surplus ever in April.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government and congressional leaders have agreed to
balance the federal budget by 2002. The total national debt
currently stands at 5.2 trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the treasury has received 1 trillion dollars
in revenues, compared to 939.2 billion dollars during the first
eight months of fiscal 1996. Spending has totaled 1.1 trillion
dollars, up from 1 trillion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury Department said the deficit in May totaled 48.5
billion dollars, down from 53.1 billion dollars a year earlier.
Receipts were 94.5 billion dollars, up from 90.1 billion dollars
in May 1996. Spending totaled 143 billion dollars, down from 143.2
billion dollars last May.
</P>
<P>
The biggest spending categories in May were Social Security,
35.1 billion dollars; Health and Human Services Department
programs, 31.5 billion dollars; interest on the national debt,
27.5 billion dollars; and the military, 25.2 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
