<HEADLINE> US Dollar Against Other Currencies Mostly Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar ended mostly
higher today, helped by a U.S.-Japanese deregulation monitoring
pact.
</P>
<P>
Currency traders interpreted the eased tension as evidence that
the United States won't pressure Japan to raise the yen's value in
order to narrow the widening Japanese trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the dollar settled at 114.81 yen, up from 113.98
yen Thursday and its highest closing level of the week. The dollar
cost 1.7275 marks, up from from 1.7237. The pound cost 1.6559 U.S.
dollars, up from 1.6488 U.S. dollars and the strongest since
January 21.
</P>
<P>
The pound also is viewed as a safe-haven alternative to the
uncertainties surrounding the planned introduction of Europe's
single currency in January 1999. Britain isn't expected to
participate initially in the currency program.
</P>
<P>
Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with late Thursday:
1.4404 Swiss francs, up from 1.4383; 5.8235 French francs, up from
5.8130; 1,688.60 Italian lire, up from 1,686.10; 1.3912 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.3875. 
</P>
</TEXT>
